1                   = Governing Body\n| leader_name1                    = [[Oakville Town Council]]\n| leader_title2                   = MPs\n| leader_name2                    = [[Anita Anand (professor)|Anita Anand]]<br>[[Pam Damoff]]\n| leader_title3                   = MPPs\n| leader_name3                    = [[Stephen Crawford (politician)|Stephen Crawford]]<br>[[Effie Triantafilopoulos]]\n| established_title               = Established\n| established_date                = 1827\n| established_title2              = \n| established_date2               = \n| established_title3              = \n| established_date3               = \n| area_magnitude                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"StatsCanProfile\"/>\n| area_land_km2                   = 138.89\n| area_water_km2                  = \n| area_water_percent              = \n| area_urban_km2                  = \n| area_metro_km2                  = \n| population_demonym              = Oakvillian\n| population_as_of                = 2016\n| population_note                 = \n| population_total                = 193,832\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=\"StatsCanProfile\">{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3524001&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&Data=Count&SearchText=Oakville&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&TABID=1&B1=All|title=Census Profile, 2016 Census - Oakville, Town [Census subdivision], Ontario and Canada [Country]|date=8 February 2016|work=Canada 2016 Census|publisher=Statistics Canada|accessdate=8 February 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211075915/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3524001&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&Data=Count&SearchText=Oakville&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&TABID=1&B1=All|url-status=live|archivedate=11 February 2017}}</ref>\n| population_density_km2          = 1314.2\n| population_urban                = \n| population_density_urban_km2    = \n| timezone                        = Eastern (EST)\n| utc_offset                      = \u22125\n| timezone_DST                    = EDT\n| utc_offset_DST                  = \u22124\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|43|27|N|79|41|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation_m                     = 173\n| postal_code_type                = [[Canadian postal code#Forward sortation areas|Forward sortation area]]\n| postal_code                     = [[List of L postal codes of Canada|L6H to L6M]]\n| area_code                       = [[Area codes 905, 289, and 365]]\n| website                         = {{URL|http://www.oakville.ca/}}\n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n\n'''Oakville''' is a town in [[southern Ontario]], located in [[Regional Municipality of Halton|Halton Region]] on [[Lake Ontario]] halfway between [[Toronto]] and [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]]. At its [[Canada 2016 Census|2016 census]] population of 193,832, it is [[List of towns in Ontario|Ontario's largest town]]. Oakville is part of the [[Greater Toronto Area]], one of the most densely populated areas of Canada.\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1793, [[Dundas Street (Toronto)|Dundas Street]] was surveyed for a military road. In 1805, the [[Legislative Assembly of Upper Canada]] bought the lands between [[Etobicoke]] and [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] from the indigenous [[Mississaugas]] people, except for the land at the mouths of [[Bronte Creek|Twelve Mile Creek (Bronte Creek)]], [[Sixteen Mile Creek (Ontario)|Sixteen Mile Creek]], and along the [[Credit River]]. In 1807, British immigrants settled the area surrounding Dundas Street as well as on the shore of [[Lake Ontario]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barclaysquare.ca/about-us/history/|title=History of Oakville|publisher=barclaysquare.ca|accessdate=August 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1820, the Crown bought the area surrounding the waterways. The area around the creeks, {{convert|960|acres|km2}}, ceded to the Crown by the Mississaugas,<ref>{{cite web| title=Illustrated Historical Atlas of Halton County (1877)| publisher=Waler & Miles|url=http://www.halinet.on.ca/localhistory/Page.asp?PageID=169| accessdate=2008-05-26}}</ref> was auctioned off to [[William Chisholm (Upper Canada)|William Chisholm]] in 1827. He left the development of the area to his son, [[Robert Kerr Chisholm]], and his brother-in-law, Merrick Thomas. Chisholm also formed shipbuilding business in Oakville Navy Street and [[Sixteen Mile Creek (Halton Region)]] and lasted until 1842, but shipbuilding in Oakville lasted into the late 20th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/culturerec/harbourheritage-essay3.html|title=Oakville Harbour Heritage|publisher=oakville.ca|accessdate=August 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cncphotoalbum.com/archive/cnchistory/history.htm|title=Oakville CN History|publisher=cncphotoalbum.com|accessdate=August 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe population in 1846 was 1,500. The community shipped large quantities of wheat and lumber via schooners and the railway. There were three churches, a grist mill and saw mill, and various small companies making threshing machines, wagons, watches, saddles, and metal goods. There were also tradesmen of various types.<ref>{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Wm. H. |date=1846 |title=Smith's Canadian Gazetteer |url=https://archive.org/details/smithscanadianga00smit |location=Toronto |publisher=H. & W. ROWSELL |page=[https://archive.org/details/smithscanadianga00smit/page/133 133]}}</ref>\n\nOakville's industries also included shipbuilding. In the 1850s, there was an economic recession and the foundry, the most important industry in town, was closed. Basket-making became a major industry in the town, and the [[Grand Trunk Railway]] was built through it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/culturerec/pioneer-essay5.html|title=Oakville Pioneers|publisher=oakville.ca|accessdate= August 14, 2017}}</ref> In 1869, the population was 2,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/provinceontario00mcevgoog#page/n164/mode/2up|title=Page 343|publisher=archive.org|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> The community was served by the [[Great Western Railway (Ontario)|Great Western Railway]] and it was a port on Lake Ontario.\n\nThe town eventually became industrialized with the opening of [[Citgo|Cities Service Canada]]\n(later [[British Petroleum Canada|BP Canada]], and now [[Petro Canada]]) and [[Shell Canada]] [[oil refineries]] (both now closed), the [[Procor]] factory (no longer manufacturing), and, most importantly, the [[Ford Motor Company of Canada|Ford Motor Company]]'s Canadian headquarters and [[Oakville Assembly|plant]], all close to the [[Canadian National Railway]] and the Queen Elizabeth Way highway between Toronto and Fort Erie (Buffalo).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lakewoodtravel.com/location/oakville|title=Oaxville Travel|publisher=lakewoodtravel.com|accessdate=August 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1962, the town of Oakville merged with its neighbouring villages ([[Bronte, Ontario|Bronte]], Palermo, Sheridan, and the remainder of [[Trafalgar Township]]) to become the new Town of Oakville, reaching northwards to [[Steeles Avenue]] in [[Milton, Ontario|Milton]]. In 1973, the restructuring of Halton County into Halton Region brought the northern border southwards to just north of the future [[Ontario Highway 407|Highway 407]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/assets/general%20-%20culture%20recreation/GeorgesSquareOakmap.pdf|title=Oakville Boundaries Map Pre 1973|publisher=oakville.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Neighbourhoods==\nOakville's Planning Department divides the town into communities.  These are based on traditional neighbourhoods.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/Offical_Plan_2006_consolidation.pdf|title=Town of Oakville Official Plan|date=2006-09-30|publisher=Town of Oakville|pages=130|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n[[File:Oakville Inn Hotel Sign.jpg|thumb|Oakville Inn Hotel sign]]\n[[File:Oakville Harbour.JPG|right|thumb|Oakville Harbour]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Neighbourhood!! Description\n|-\n| Old Oakville|| Old Oakville (downtown) is located in South-Central Oakville along the shore of [[Lake Ontario]], and is centred on Oakville Harbour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/OldOakville.pdf|title=Old Oakville Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n| Kerr Village|| Kerr Village is a section of downtown located just west of the Old Village around Kerr Street between Speers Rd and [[Lakeshore Road]].\n|-\n| Bronte|| [[Bronte, Ontario|Bronte]] is located in Southwest Oakville along the shore of Lake Ontario.  It is a community centred on Bronte Harbour and includes the Coronation Park district to its east.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/Bronte.pdf|title=Bronte Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n| Eastlake|| Eastlake is located in Southeast Oakville along the shore of Lake Ontario.  It is bordered on the west by Morrison Creek, to the north by Cornwall Road, and to the east by [[Mississauga]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/Eastlake.pdf|title=Eastlake Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|Clearview ||Clearview is located in Centre East Oakville. It is located on the Oakville-Mississauga border<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/Clearview.pdf|title=Clearview Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n| College Park|| College Park is located between [[Sixteen Mile Creek (Ontario)|Sixteen Mile Creek]] and just east of Trafalgar Road, from the [[Queen Elizabeth Way]] north to Upper Middle Road.  It surrounds Sheridan College.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/CollegePark.pdf|title=College Park Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n| Iroquois Ridge North||Iroquois Ridge North is located in North East Oakville between Upper Middle Road and Dundas Street.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/IRNorth.pdf|title=Iroquois Ridge North Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|Iroquois Ridge South ||Iroquois Ridge South is located in North East Oakville.  The Falgarwood area is located in the southern end of the Iroquois Ridge South community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/IRSouth.pdf|title=Iroquois Ridge South Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|Glen Abbey ||Glen Abbey is located in West Oakville, with Third Line being the major artery of the community.  It is a large area west of the [[Glen Abbey Golf Course]], home of the [[Canadian Open (golf)|Canadian Open]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/GlenAbbey.pdf|title=Glen Abbey Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref> Birth place of [[Andrew|Andrew Conway]]\n|-\n|Palermo ||[[Palermo, Ontario|Palermo]] is located in Northwest Oakville.  It is a small community centred on the intersection of Dundas Street and Bronte Road (Highway 25).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/PalermoWest.pdf|title=Palermo Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|River Oaks ||River Oaks is located in North-Central Oakville.  It includes the Oak Park development.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/RiverOaks.pdf|title=River Oaks Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|Uptown Core ||Uptown Core is located in North Centre Oakville.  It includes the area on either side of Trafalgar Road between Dundas Street and Glenashton Drive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/UptownCore.pdf|title=Uptown Core Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|West Oak Trails ||West Oak Trails is located in North Centre West Oakville on the north side of Upper Middle Road.  It is a newer development than the other communities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/WestOakTrails.pdf|title=West Oak Trails Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|title       = Oakville\n|type        = Canada\n|align       = right\n|width       = \n|state       = \n|shading     = \n|percentages = \n|footnote    = \n|1841|550\n|1871|1684\n|1901|1643\n|1911|2372\n|1921|3298\n|1931|3857\n|1941|4115\n|1951|6910\n|1961|10366\n|1971|61483\n|1981|75773\n|1991|114670\n|[[Canada 1996 Census|1996]]|128405\n|[[Canada 2001 Census|2001]]|144738\n|[[Canada 2006 Census|2006]]|165613\n|[[Canada 2011 Census|2011]]|182520\n|[[Canada 2016 Census|2016]]|193832\n}}\n\nAccording to the 2016 Canadian Census, Oakville had 193,832 residents. This represents a 6.2% increase since the 2011 Census.<ref name=\"StatsCanProfile\" />\n\nAccording to the 2006 census, Oakville had a younger population than Canada as a whole. Minors (youth under 19 years of age) totalled 28.1 percent of the population compared to pensioners who number 11.7 percent. This compares with the Canadian average of 24.4 percent (minors) and 13.7 percent (pensioners).<ref name=\"CensusCommunity\">{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census06/data/profiles/community/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3524001&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Oakville&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=|title=Community highlights for Oakville|date=2008-04-30|work=2006 Census Data|publisher=Statistics Canada|accessdate=2008-06-04}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"right\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n!Ethnic Origin<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=FED&Code1=35060&Data=Count&SearchText=Oakville&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=Ethnic%20origin&B1=All&Custom=&amp;TABID=1|title= NHS Profile, Oakville, Ontario, 2011|date=2013-09-11|work=2011 Census Data|publisher=Statistics Canada|accessdate=2015-02-01}}</ref>\n!Population\n!Percent\n|-\n|[[English people|English]]\n|45,435\n|24.89%\n|-\n|[[Scottish people|Scottish]]\n|31,870\n|17.46%\n|-\n|[[Irish people|Irish]]\n|30,795\n|18.72%\n|-\n|[[Italian people|Italian]]\n|16,970\n|9.30%\n|-\n|[[German people|German]]\n|15,410\n|8.44%\n|-\n|[[French people|French]]\n|14,580\n|7.99%\n|-\n|[[Polish people|Polish]]\n|10,240\n|5.61%\n|-\n|[[Indo-Canadians|East Indian]]\n|9,605\n|5.26%\n|-\n|[[Chinese Canadian|Chinese]]\n|7,785\n|4.27%\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Canada 2016 Census!! Population !! % of Total Population\n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\" | [[Visible minority]] group<br><small>Source:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=1209034&Geo2=CD&Code2=1209&Data=Count&SearchText=Oakville&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1 |title=Community Profiles from the 2016 Census, Statistics Canada - Census Subdivision |publisher=2.statcan.gc.ca |date=December 6, 2010 |accessdate=April 13, 2013}}</ref></small> \n| [[South Asia]]n || 17,095 || {{Percentage | 17095 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n|| [[Chinese Canadian|Chinese]] || 13,435 || {{Percentage | 13435 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Arab Canadian|Arab]] || 6,095 || {{Percentage | 6095 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Black Canadians|Black]] || 5,520 || {{Percentage | 5520 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Filipino Canadian|Filipino]] || 3,710 || {{Percentage | 3710 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Latin American Canadian|Latin American]] || 3,595 || {{Percentage | 3595 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Korean Canadian|Korean]] || 3,080 || {{Percentage | 