SD&Code1=3524001&Geo2=CD&Code2=3524&Data=Count&SearchText=oakville&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1|title=Oakville, Ontario (Code 3524001) and Halton, Ontario (Code 3524) (table) Census Profile|last=Statistics Canada|date=24 October 2012|work=2011 Census|publisher=Statistics Canada Catalogue no. 98-316-XWE|location=Ottawa|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212192629/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3524001&Geo2=CD&Code2=3524&Data=Count&SearchText=oakville&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1|url-status=live|archivedate=12 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n79.4% of residents stated their religion as Christian, almost evenly split between Roman Catholics and Protestants. Non-Christian religions include [[Islam]]: 2.0%, [[Hinduism]]: 1.3%, [[Sikhism]]: 1.1%, and [[Judaism]]: 0.7%. 14% indicated no religion.\n\nThe median household income is $118, 671,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.halton.ca/cms/One.aspx?portalId=8310&pageId=109529|title=Median Household|publisher=halton.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> with an average house value of $1,118,572.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.omdreb.on.ca/news/market-watch|title=Average House Value|publisher=omdreb.on.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nThe top employers in Oakville include:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/assets/general%20-%20business/Top_100_Employers.pdf|title=Oakville Top 100 employers|publisher=oakville.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Company / organization'''\n! Employees\n! Sector\n|-\n| [[Halton Catholic District School Board]]||4,592||Education\n|-\n|[[Ford Motor Company of Canada]]||4,500||Head Office & Automobile Manufacturing Plant\n|-\n|[[Halton District School Board]]||2,393||Education\n|-\n|[[Halton Healthcare]]||2,290||Healthcare Services\n|-\n|[[Regional Municipality of Halton]]||2,054||Regional Government\n|-\n|[[Sheridan College]]||1,856||Post-Secondary Institution\n|-\n|The Corporation of the Town of Oakville||1,144||Municipal Government\n|-\n|}\n\n==Climate==\nLike much of Southern Ontario, Oakville has a humid continental climate with cold, but not extreme, winters and warm summers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.climate-data.org/location/47343/|title=Oakville Climate Data|publisher=climate-data.org|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n{{Oakville weatherbox}}\n\n==Sports==\n===Soccer===\nThe [[Oakville Blue Devils]] of [[League 1 Ontario]] is a professional soccer team. The Blue Devils are affiliated with the Oakville Soccer Club, which is the largest soccer club in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidehalton.com/sports-story/5799168-oakville-soccer-club-granted-membership-in-opdl|title=Oakville Soccer Club|publisher=insidehalton.com|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> Oakville boasts over 60 soccer fields and a Soccer Club Facility with a 2 star full size FIFA Certified indoor soccer pitch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakvillesoccer.ca/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=651:pine-glen-soccer-centre-corporate-rentals&catid=136:indoor-news&Itemid=71|title=Oakville Pine Glen Soccer Facility|publisher=oakvillesoccer.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Lacrosse===\nOakville is home to the headquarters and practice facilities of the [[Toronto Rock]] professional box lacrosse team competing in the National Lacrosse League. Oakville is also home to the 3rd largest minor lacrosse association in Ontario: The Oakville Minor Lacrosse Association has more than 1,500 players and competes in multiple classes and multiple divisions. The town also has the [[Oakville Buzz]], a [[OLA Junior A Lacrosse League|Junior \"A\"]] [[box lacrosse|lacrosse]] team who won the [[Founders Cup]] in 2006. The current rep lacrosse team is the Oakville Hawks.{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\n===Hockey===\n[[File:Sixteen Mile Sports Complex (NE View) - Oakville, ON.jpg|thumb|Oakville Blades home game]]\nThe [[Oakville Blades]] is a [[Ontario Provincial Junior A Hockey League|Tier II Junior \"A\"]] franchise since 1966, and a \"AAA\" hockey system. The current rep hockey team for boys  in Oakville is Oakville Rangers, who are the 2-time defending champions for the Midget \"AAA\" group. For girls, there is the Oakville Hornets, who are the largest female hockey association in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://moha.ca|title=Oakville Hockey|publisher=moha.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Skating===\nSkate Oakville, which is headquartered at Oakville's Sixteen Mile Creek Sports Complex, is the largest skating club in Canada,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidehalton.com/sports-story/4869180-skate-oakville-figure-skating-season-already-underway/|title=Oakville Figure Skating Season Underway|publisher=insidehalton.com|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> providing learn to skate lessons, recreational figure skating programs, competitive training, and 10 synchronized skating teams.<ref>{{cite web|title=Skate Oakville|url=https://www.skateoakville.ca/|website=Skate Oakville.ca|publisher=Skate Oakville|accessdate=2015-11-03}}</ref>\n\n===Baseball===\nBaseball is represented in Oakville by two organizations, Oakville Little League and the OMBA (Oakville Minor Baseball Association).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.insidehalton.com/sports-story/4497626-oakville-baseball-associations-to-open-2014-seasons-next-saturday|title=Oakville Basketball associations to Open|publisher=insidehalton.com|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOakville Little League is the largest [[Little League Baseball|Little League]] organization in Canada. In 2018, there were over 1,150 young people playing across eight divisions and over 90 teams, including 7 All-Star teams. Oakville Little League also fields six All-Star (Rep) teams, known as the Oakville Whitecaps. The 12U and 14U Whitecaps teams compete annually to play in the [[Little League World Series]] and [[Junior League World Series]], respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehalton.com/community-story/5803168-junior-world-series-everything-and-more-for-oakville-whitecaps/|title=Junior World Series 'everything, and more' for Oakville Whitecaps|publisher=insidehalton.com|accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe OMBA (Oakville Minor Baseball Association) was established in 1963.  It offers 3 levels of baseball to children and youth in Oakville:  House League, Select and Rep.  OMBA runs the Oakville A's, the official Town Rep baseball playing in the Central Ontario Baseball Association (COBA) system.\n===Golf===\n[[Glen Abbey Golf Course]], site of several [[Canadian Open (golf)|Canadian Open]] professional golf championships and many other amateur tournaments, is also located in Oakville.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2018/11/08/fight-for-oakvilles-glen-abbey-golf-course-heading-to-ontario-court-of-appeal.html |title=Fight for Oakville\u2019s Glen Abbey Golf Course heading to Ontario Court of Appeal |date=8 November 2018 |website=Toronto Start |publisher=Metroland News |access-date=8 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Canoeing===\nAnother sport Oakville is well known for is its [[Burloak Canoe Club]], where they have had Olympians come out of, such as [[Adam van Koeverden]], [[Mark Oldershaw]] and [[Larry Cain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://burloakcanoe.com/about-us/wall-of-fame/|title=Burloak Canoe|publisher=burloakcanoe.com|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n\n===Downtown Oakville Jazz Festival===\nThe [[Downtown Oakville Jazz Festival]] is an annual summer jazz festival, since 1992.  The event includes performances at a number of stages along [[Lakeshore Road]] in downtown Oakville.  The event is free to the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://visitoakville.com/events/downtown-oakville-jazz-festival/|title=Visit Oakville|publisher=City Of Oakville|accessdate=Aug 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Waterfront Festival===\nBeginning in 1982, Oakville's Coronation Park played host to the annual [[Oakville Waterfront Festival]].  Among a range of events, the festival included small amusement park rides, arts and crafts, food and drinks, free concerts headlined by Canadian bands, and nightly fireworks displays.  The Waterfront Festival took place in late June of each year until 2010, when it was cancelled due to financial difficulties,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidehalton.com/news/article/437645|title=Plug pulled on Oakville Waterfront Festival|publisher=InsideHalton|date=2009-12-03}}</ref> despite having annual attendance of up to 100,000 visitors. It returned in August 2013,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lea|first=David|title=Oakville's Waterfront Festival returning in August|url=http://www.insidehalton.com/news/article/1589407--oakville-s-waterfront-festival-returning-in-august|work=insidehalton.com|accessdate=23 April 2013}}</ref> which was the final festival to date.\n\n===Kerrfest===\nThe Kerrfest is an annual outdoor music festival that takes place in early September in Oakville. Having begun in 2014, the event includes free performances and is open to the public, located at Westwood Park.<ref>https://www.inhalton.com/everything-you-need-to-know-about-kerrfest-in-oakville-this-weekend</ref>\n\n===For the Love of the Arts Festival===\nThe For the Love of the Arts Festival is an annual event taking place in the late spring in Oakville. Inaugurated in 2002, the event is hosted by CommUnity Arts Space (originally known as Music and Art Shared Space who initiated the festival), a local umbrella group advocating for shared physical space for Oakville's arts and cultural groups.<ref>{{cite web|title=In Ontario: Oakville Music And Art Shared Space|url=http://www.inontario.ca/ArtsEntertainment/OakvilleMusicArt/tabid/178/Default.aspx|website=In Ontario}}</ref>  Currently the only such multi-disciplinary community festival of its kind in Oakville, the event serves to showcase local talent, skills, crafts, literary art, dance performances, theatre groups and music performances.  The event is intended as a symbolic presentation of a \"shared space\" and is entirely sponsored by local corporate and private donations.<ref>{{cite web|title=For Love Of The Arts Festival|url=https://oakville.snapd.com/event/168969#/|website=Snapd Oakville|accessdate=Aug 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Canadian Open===\nThe [[Glen Abbey Golf Course]] is the home to the [[Golf Canada]] and the [[Canadian Golf Hall of Fame]].  It has hosted 31 [[Canadian Open (golf)|Canadian Open]] Championships since 1977, most recently in July 2018. Glen Abbey is owned by [[Clublink]], which was planning to demolish the golf course in order to build residential and commercial units, if it is successful in overturning the city's decision to prevent the development. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/golf/2018/07/20/this-year-could-be-glen-abbeys-last-as-owners-plan-redevelopment-for-condos-and-offices.html |title=This year could be Glen Abbey\u2019s last as owners plan redevelopment for condos and offices |date=20 July 2018 |website=Toronto Start |publisher=Metroland News |access-date=27 October 2018}}</ref>  In 2018, the company achieved some success in its efforts against the town, after a Superior Court ruled against the town's attempts to block the redevelopment. The Local Planning Appeal Tribunal (LPAT) will hold two hearing in 2019 on ClubLink\u2019s appeal of the town's decision. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/9080143-town-of-oakville-dealt-another-courtroom-setback-in-fight-to-save-glen-abbey-golf-course/ |title=Town of Oakville dealt another courtroom setback in fight to save Glen Abbey Golf Course |date=12 December 2018 |website=Inside Halton |publisher=Metroland News |access-date=15 December 2018|quote=Conservation plan and related bylaws struck down by Ontario Superior Court of Justice}}</ref>\n\nThe 2019 and 2023 events were scheduled to be held at the Hamilton Golf and Country Club but the Canadian Open may again be held at Glen Abbey in some future years if the redevelopment is not allowed to proceed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/golf/hamilton-to-host-canadian-open-in-2019-2023-1.4694543|title=Canadian Open returning to Hamilton in 2019, 2023 |date=6 June 2018 |publisher=CBC Sports |access-date=15 December 2018|quote=Applebaum said Golf Canada has not ruled out returning to Glen Abbey in the future but is \"speaking with a variety of people\" about hosting 2020, 2021, and 2022.}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n{{see also|List of schools in Oakville, Ontario}}\n\nElementary schools and high schools in Oakville are a mix of private and public schools, with one of the highest ratios of private schools to student population in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.robkelly.ca/Our-Communities---Oakville.html|title=Oakville School Communities|publisher=robkelley.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> Oakville is covered by the [[Halton District School Board]], [[Halton Catholic District School Board]], [[Conseil scolaire Viamonde]], and [[Conseil scolaire catholique MonAvenir]]. [[St. Thomas Aquinas Catholic Secondary School (Oakville)]] and [[White Oaks Secondary School]] both offer the [[International Baccalaureate]] Program.\n\nThe town is home to [[Appleby College]], a private school for grades seven to twelve, established in 1911<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.appleby.on.ca|title=Appleby Website|publisher=appleby.on.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> as well as [[St. Mildred's-Lightbourn School]], an independent all-girls school. Oakville is also home to the Trafalgar Campus of [[Sheridan College]], primarily an arts and business studies institute, and Oakville's only higher education facility.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sheridancollege.ca|title=Sheridan College Website|publisher=sheridancollege.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\n\n===Municipal and regional===\nAt the municipal level, the governing body is the [[Oakville Town Council]] consisting of a [[List of mayors of Oakville, Ontario|mayor]] (currently [[Rob Burton]]) and fourteen [[councillors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.hipinfo.info/record/OAK1575|title=Members of Oakville Town Council|publisher=search.hipinfp.info|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>  The town is divided into seven [[Ward (politics)|wards]], with two councillors elected by residents of each ward.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/assets/general%20-%20town%20hall/WBR-ASC-11nov15.pdf|title=Oakville Ward Review|publisher=oakville.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn each ward one councillor represents the ward solely on Oakville Town Council, and the other is a member of the 21-member governing council of the [[Regional Municipality of Halton]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/assets/general%20-%20town%20hall/WBR-ASC-11nov15.pdf|title=Oakville Governing Council|publisher=oakville.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> in addition to being a member of the 13-member Town Council.\n\n===Provincial===\nOakville is situated in two provincial [[Electoral district (Canada)|ridings]] which use the same boundaries as the federal ridings and are currently represented provincially by:\n\n* [[Oakville (provincial electoral district)|Oakville]]: [[Stephen Crawford (politician)|Stephen Crawford]] ([[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|Conservative]])<ref name=\"Who are the Halton winners? All PC\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/8658442-who-are-the-halton-winners-all-pc/|title=Who are the Halton winners? All PC|date=2018-06-07|work=InsideHalton.com|access-date=2018-07-14|language=en-CA}}</ref>\n*[[Oakville North\u2014Burlington (provincial electoral district)|Oakville North-Burlington]]: [[Effie Triantafilopoulos]] ([[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|Conservative]])<ref name=\"Who are the Halton winners? All PC\"/>\n\n===Federal===\nOakville is situated in two federal [[Electoral district (Canada)|ridings]] which are currently represented by:\n\n* [[Oakville (electoral district)|Oakville]]: [[Anita Anand (professor)|Anita Anand]] ([[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]])<ref>https://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/9655754--collective-victory-liberal-anita-anand-is-the-oakville-riding-s-new-mp/</ref>\n* [[Oakville North\u2014Burlington|Oakville North-Burlington]]: [[Pam Damoff]] ([[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/5968252-updated-liberal-pam-damoff-takes-new-oakville-north-burlington-mp-seat/|title=Liberal Pam Damoff takes new Oakville North\u2014Burlington MP seat|last=Le|first=Julia|date=20 October 2015|work=Oakville Beaver|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029070812/http://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/5968252-updated-liberal-pam-damoff-takes-new-oakville-north-burlington-mp-seat/|url-status=live|archivedate=29 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Arts and culture==\n===Oakville Centre for the Performing Arts===\n[[Image:Oakville-Centre-for-Performing-Arts.JPG|thumb|right|Oakville Centre for the Performing Arts]]The [[Oakville Centre for the Performing Arts]] houses several performances by local and international artists. It is also the performing venue for the [[Oakville Symphony Orchestra]], the [[Oakville Children's Choir]] and the [[Oakville Ballet Company]]. The Oakville Arts Council provides further artistic talents in the town showcasing films, literary figures and visual arts.\n\n===The Oakville Children's Choir===\nThe [[Oakville Children's Choir]] has been in business since 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehalton.com/whatson-story/5640147-oakville-children-s-choir-ends-season-with-concert-award/|title=Oakville Children's Choir wins awards|publisher=insidehalton.com|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Oakville Galleries ===\nOakville Galleries is a not-for-profit art museum that exhibits contemporary art, cares for a permanent collection and delivers public programming. Its exhibition spaces are located on two sites: Gairloch Gardens and Centennial Square.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oakvillegalleries.com/about/mission|title=Gallery website|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n==Media==\nOakville is primarily served by media based in Toronto with markets in the [[Greater Toronto Area]] (GTA) that cover most of the news in the GTA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/townhall/nr-17feb03.html|title=Oakville GTA|publisher=oakville.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> One regional newspaper, the ''[[Oakville Beaver]]'', is published once weekly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://search.hipinfo.info/record/OAK1249|title=Oakville Beaver|website=search.hipinfo.info|access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehalton.com/oakville-on/|title=Oakville Beaver|publisher=insidehalton.com|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\nThe monthly magazines Neighbours of Joshua Creek, Neighbours of Glen Abbey and Neighbours of Olde Oakville serve three key neighbourhoods.\n\nThe town also has two specialty radio stations: AM 1250 [[CJYE]], a [[Christian music]] station<ref>{{cite web|url=https://radio-locator.com/info/CJYE-AM|title=AM 1250 Radio Locator|publisher=radio-locator.com|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> and AM 1320 [[CJMR]], a [[Multiculturalism|Multicultural]] station.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tunein.com/radio/CJMR-1320-s31220/|title=AM 1320 Radio Tune In|publisher=tunein.com|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe following national cable television station also broadcast from Oakville:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yellowpages.ca/search/si/1/Television+Stations+%26+Broadcasting+Companies/Oakville+ON|title=Television Broadcasting from Oakville|publisher=yellowpages.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n*[[The Weather Network]] has broadcast nationally from Oakville since 2005\n* The Hamilton-based television station [[CHCH-DT]] serves [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]], [[Halton Region, Ontario|Halton]] and [[Niagara Region, Ontario|Niagara]], thus including Oakville. CHCH recently closed its Halton Bureau (due to budget considerations) which was located in downtown Oakville.\n*[[TVCogeco]] from the studio in the [[Cogeco Cable]] Headquarters at Harvester Road & Burloak Drive, just inside of [[Burlington, Ontario|Burlington]].\n\n==Transportation==\n[[Oakville Transit]] provides local bus service. [[GO Transit]] commuter rail and bus service operates from [[Bronte GO Station|Bronte]] and [[Oakville GO Station|Oakville]] stations. [[Via Rail]] services along the line between [[Quebec City \u2013 Windsor Corridor|Windsor and Quebec corridor]], and operates from Oakville station.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.viarail.ca/en/travel-info/transport-services/intermodality/go-transit|title=Oakville Transportation Info|publisher=viarail.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Queen Elizabeth Way]], [[Ontario Highway 403]], and the [[407 ETR]] highways run through Oakville.\n\n==Emergency services==\n[[Policing]] in Oakville is performed by the [[Halton Regional Police Service]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrps.on.ca/Locations/Oakville/pages/default.aspx|title=Oakville|work=Halton Region Police Service|publisher=Regional Municipality of Halton Police Services Board|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304114134/http://www.hrps.on.ca/Locations/Oakville/Pages/default.aspx|url-status=dead|archivedate=4 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Fire service]] is provided by the town through the Oakville Fire Department with eight [[fire station]]s.\n\nThe Town of Oakville's Waters Air Rescue Force (TOWARF) is a volunteer organization that provides marine search and rescue service in Western Lake Ontario. It was founded in 1954 and was a charter member of the [[Canadian Coast Guard Auxiliary]].<ref name=towarf>{{cite web|title=TOWARF|url=http://www.towarf.com/|work=TOWARF \u2013 Town of Oakville Water Air Rescue Force|accessdate=2011-02-26}}</ref>\n\n==Commerce==\n[[File:Tim Hortons corporate headquarters - 01.jpg|thumb|[[Tim Hortons]] headquarters]]\n\n===Employers===\n\n[[Tim Hortons]] (moving to Toronto)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/real_estate/2018/04/17/tim-hortons-to-move-its-canadian-head-office.html|title=Tim Hortons to move its Canadian head office {{!}} The Star|work=thestar.com|access-date=2018-07-14|language=en}}</ref> and [[Mattamy Homes]] are based in Oakville while [[Siemens]], [[Ford Motor Company of Canada|The Ford Motor Company,]] and MADD Canada have their head Canadian offices in the town. Many Oakville residents work in advanced manufacturing at large facilities operated by [[UTC Aerospace Systems]] and [[General Electric]].<ref name=\"Top Employers By Sector\">{{cite web|title=Top Employers By Sector|url=http://www.oakville.ca/economicdevelopment/top-employers.html|website=oakville.ca|publisher=City Of Oakville|accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nMany Oakville companies fall under the [[List of life sciences|life science umbrella]], with an emphasis on [[Pharmaceutical industry|pharmaceuticals]] and [[elder care]].<ref name=\"Top Employers By Sector\" /> There are also a number of retirement homes in the city.<ref name=\"Top Employers By Sector\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Retirement Homes Oakville|url=http://www.comfortlife.ca/retirement-communities/oakville-retirement-homes|website=Comfort Life|publisher=Our Kids Media|accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs Oakville is considered part of the [[Greater Toronto Area]] it is common for residents to commute to jobs in [[Toronto]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Living In Toronto What's It Like|url=http://www.livingin-canada.com/living-in-toronto.html|website=Living In Canada|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Oakville Place===\nThe Oakville Place Shopping Centre is an indoor shopping mall in Oakville that opened in 1981.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.eyeonsheridan.com/oakville-place-is-the-place-to-be/|last= Kukolic|first= Kristina|title= Oakville Place Is The Place To Be|publisher= Eye on Sheridan|date= 2010-12-09|accessdate= 2015-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= http://www.bramptonguardian.com/news-story/3910504-ceiling-collapses-at-oakville-place/ |title= Ceiling collapses at The Bay in Oakville Place|last= Lea|first= David|newspaper= Oakville Beaver|date= 2013-07-25|accessdate= 2015-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= http://thesheridansun.ca/blog/2014/03/24/oakville-place-is-just-dancing-this-march-break/ |newspaper= The Sheridan Sun|title= Oakville Place is Just Dancing this March Break|last= Paisley|first= Dylan|date= 2014-03-24|accessdate= 2015-05-25}}</ref>  The mall is approximately {{convert|42000|m2|sqft|-3}}.<ref name = \"Maitland1990\">{{cite book | first= Barry |last= Maitland | title = The new architecture of the retail mall | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Cg9UAAAAMAAJ | accessdate = 2014-06-19 | year = 1990 | location= New York|publisher = Van Nostrand Reinhold|isbn= 9781854548153|oclc= 23726658}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=tA1UAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Oakville+Place%22&dq=%22Oakville+Place%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=lemfU6jsOsLZoAT43YKoCA&ved=0CCMQ6AEwAjgU |title= Shopping malls: planning and design|first= Barry|last= Maitland|year= 1985|location= New York|publisher= Nichols|page= 173|isbn= 9780893972264|oclc= 11971331}}</ref>\n\n===Smart Centre Oakville===\nSmart Centre Oakville is a retail mall located in the northeast end of Oakville.\n\n==Sister cities==\nOakville is twinned with the cities of [[Dorval]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/454427461.html?dids=454427461:454427461&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=May+28%2C+1992&author=Bobbi-Jean+MacKinnon+Toronto+Star&pub=Toronto+Star&desc=People-to-people+appeal+for+Canada+growing&pqatl=google|title=People-to-people appeal for Canada growing|last=MacKinnon|first=Bobbi-Jean|date=1992-05-28|work=Toronto Star|page=MA.6|accessdate=2009-08-28}}</ref> in Quebec, and [[Neyagawa]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/sistercity.htm|title=Oakville's Sister City \u2013 Neyagawa, Japan|work=Oakville.ca|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2009-08-28|archivedate=2009-08-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814030530/http://www.oakville.ca/sistercity.htm}}</ref> Japan. The Town of Oakville has named two major streets after these cities.  In 2015, [[Huai'an]], China became a sister city to Oakville.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Town of Oakville forms sister city bond with Huai\u2019an, China|publisher=Town of Oakville|date=24 Aug 2015|url=https://www.oakville.ca/townhall/nr-15aug24.html|accessdate=1 August 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628064647/https://www.oakville.ca/townhall/nr-15aug24.html|archivedate=28 Jun 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Ontario}}\n* [[:Category:People from Oakville, Ontario]]\n* [[List of people from Oakville, Ontario]]\n* [[List of schools in Oakville, Ontario]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Oakville}}\n{{wikivoyage|Oakville (Ontario)|Oakville, Ontario}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.oakville.ca/ }}\n\n{{Geographic location|\nNorthwest=[[Milton, Ontario|Milton]]|\nSouthwest=[[Burlington, Ontario|Burlington]]|\nCenter=Oakville|\nNortheast=[[Mississauga]]|\nSoutheast=''[[Lake Ontario]]''|}}\n\n{{Oakville, Ontario}}\n{{Halton region}}\n{{Greater Toronto Area}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Lower-tier municipalities in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Oakville, Ontario| ]]\n[[Category:Populated places on Lake Ontario in Canada]]\n[[Category:1827 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Underground Railroad]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1827]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Oakville\n| official_name                   = Town of Oakville\n| native_name                     = \n| nickname                        = \n| motto                           = ''Avancez'' (\"Go forward\")<ref>{{cite web| title=Coat of Arms| publisher=Town of Oakville| url=http://www.oakville.ca/coatofarms.htm| accessdate=2007-12-30}}</ref>\n| settlement_type                 = [[List of towns in Ontario|Town]] ([[List of municipalities in Ontario#Lower-tier municipalities|lower-tier]])\n| image_skyline                   = Oakville-Ontario-Downtown.JPG\n| imagesize                       = \n| image_caption                   = Downtown Oakville\n| image_flag                      = \n| flag_size                       = \n| image_seal                      = \n| seal_size                       = \n| image_shield                    = Oakville shield.jpg\n| shield_size                     = 100x90px\n| image_blank_emblem              = Logo_of_Oakville.gif\n| blank_emblem_size               = 100x90px\n| image_map                       = Oakville, Ontario Location.png\n| mapsize                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = Canada Southern Ontario\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = Canada\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Provinces of Canada|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Ontario]]\n| subdivision_type2               = Region\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Regional Municipality of Halton|Halton]]\n| subdivision_type3               = [[Ward (politics)|Wards]]\n| subdivision_name3               = 7\n| subdivision_type4               = Neighbourhoods\n| subdivision_name4               = 12\n| government_type                 = \n| leader_title                    = Town Mayor\n| leader_name                     = [[Rob Burton]]\n| leader_title1                   = Governing Body\n| leader_name1                    = [[Oakville Town Council]]\n| leader_title2                   = MPs\n| leader_name2                    = [[Anita Anand (professor)|Anita Anand]]<br>[[Pam Damoff]]\n| leader_title3                   = MPPs\n| leader_name3                    = [[Stephen Crawford (politician)|Stephen Crawford]]<br>[[Effie Triantafilopoulos]]\n| established_title               = Established\n| established_date                = 1827\n| established_title2              = \n| established_date2               = \n| established_title3              = \n| established_date3               = \n| area_magnitude                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"StatsCanProfile\"/>\n| area_land_km2                   = 138.89\n| area_water_km2                  = \n| area_water_percent              = \n| area_urban_km2                  = \n| area_metro_km2                  = \n| population_demonym              = Oakvillian\n| population_as_of                = 2016\n| population_note                 = \n| population_total                = 193,832\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=\"StatsCanProfile\">{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3524001&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&Data=Count&SearchText=Oakville&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&TABID=1&B1=All|title=Census Profile, 2016 Census - Oakville, Town [Census subdivision], Ontario and Canada [Country]|date=8 February 2016|work=Canada 2016 Census|publisher=Statistics Canada|accessdate=8 February 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211075915/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3524001&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&Data=Count&SearchText=Oakville&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&TABID=1&B1=All|url-status=live|archivedate=11 February 2017}}</ref>\n| population_density_km2          = 1314.2\n| population_urban                = \n| population_density_urban_km2    = \n| timezone                        = Eastern (EST)\n| utc_offset                      = \u22125\n| timezone_DST                    = EDT\n| utc_offset_DST                  = \u22124\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|43|27|N|79|41|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation_m                     = 173\n| postal_code_type                = [[Canadian postal code#Forward sortation areas|Forward sortation area]]\n| postal_code                     = [[List of L postal codes of Canada|L6H to L6M]]\n| area_code                       = [[Area codes 905, 289, and 365]]\n| website                         = {{URL|http://www.oakville.ca/}}\n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n\n'''Oakville''' is a town in [[southern Ontario]], located in [[Regional Municipality of Halton|Halton Region]] on [[Lake Ontario]] halfway between [[Toronto]] and [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]]. At its [[Canada 2016 Census|2016 census]] population of 193,832, it is [[List of towns in Ontario|Ontario's largest town]]. Oakville is part of the [[Greater Toronto Area]], one of the most densely populated areas of Canada.\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1793, [[Dundas Street (Toronto)|Dundas Street]] was surveyed for a military road. In 1805, the [[Legislative Assembly of Upper Canada]] bought the lands between [[Etobicoke]] and [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] from the indigenous [[Mississaugas]] people, except for the land at the mouths of [[Bronte Creek|Twelve Mile Creek (Bronte Creek)]], [[Sixteen Mile Creek (Ontario)|Sixteen Mile Creek]], and along the [[Credit River]]. In 1807, British immigrants settled the area surrounding Dundas Street as well as on the shore of [[Lake Ontario]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barclaysquare.ca/about-us/history/|title=History of Oakville|publisher=barclaysquare.ca|accessdate=August 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1820, the Crown bought the area surrounding the waterways. The area around the creeks, {{convert|960|acres|km2}}, ceded to the Crown by the Mississaugas,<ref>{{cite web| title=Illustrated Historical Atlas of Halton County (1877)| publisher=Waler & Miles|url=http://www.halinet.on.ca/localhistory/Page.asp?PageID=169| accessdate=2008-05-26}}</ref> was auctioned off to [[William Chisholm (Upper Canada)|William Chisholm]] in 1827. He left the development of the area to his son, [[Robert Kerr Chisholm]], and his brother-in-law, Merrick Thomas. Chisholm also formed shipbuilding business in Oakville Navy Street and [[Sixteen Mile Creek (Halton Region)]] and lasted until 1842, but shipbuilding in Oakville lasted into the late 20th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/culturerec/harbourheritage-essay3.html|title=Oakville Harbour Heritage|publisher=oakville.ca|accessdate=August 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cncphotoalbum.com/archive/cnchistory/history.htm|title=Oakville CN History|publisher=cncphotoalbum.com|accessdate=August 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe population in 1846 was 1,500. The community shipped large quantities of wheat and lumber via schooners and the railway. There were three churches, a grist mill and saw mill, and various small companies making threshing machines, wagons, watches, saddles, and metal goods. There were also tradesmen of various types.<ref>{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Wm. H. |date=1846 |title=Smith's Canadian Gazetteer |url=https://archive.org/details/smithscanadianga00smit |location=Toronto |publisher=H. & W. ROWSELL |page=[https://archive.org/details/smithscanadianga00smit/page/133 133]}}</ref>\n\nOakville's industries also included shipbuilding. In the 1850s, there was an economic recession and the foundry, the most important industry in town, was closed. Basket-making became a major industry in the town, and the [[Grand Trunk Railway]] was built through it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/culturerec/pioneer-essay5.html|title=Oakville Pioneers|publisher=oakville.ca|accessdate= August 14, 2017}}</ref> In 1869, the population was 2,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/provinceontario00mcevgoog#page/n164/mode/2up|title=Page 343|publisher=archive.org|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> The community was served by the [[Great Western Railway (Ontario)|Great Western Railway]] and it was a port on Lake Ontario.\n\nThe town eventually became industrialized with the opening of [[Citgo|Cities Service Canada]]\n(later [[British Petroleum Canada|BP Canada]], and now [[Petro Canada]]) and [[Shell Canada]] [[oil refineries]] (both now closed), the [[Procor]] factory (no longer manufacturing), and, most importantly, the [[Ford Motor Company of Canada|Ford Motor Company]]'s Canadian headquarters and [[Oakville Assembly|plant]], all close to the [[Canadian National Railway]] and the Queen Elizabeth Way highway between Toronto and Fort Erie (Buffalo).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lakewoodtravel.com/location/oakville|title=Oaxville Travel|publisher=lakewoodtravel.com|accessdate=August 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1962, the town of Oakville merged with its neighbouring villages ([[Bronte, Ontario|Bronte]], Palermo, Sheridan, and the remainder of [[Trafalgar Township]]) to become the new Town of Oakville, reaching northwards to [[Steeles Avenue]] in [[Milton, Ontario|Milton]]. In 1973, the restructuring of Halton County into Halton Region brought the northern border southwards to just north of the future [[Ontario Highway 407|Highway 407]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/assets/general%20-%20culture%20recreation/GeorgesSquareOakmap.pdf|title=Oakville Boundaries Map Pre 1973|publisher=oakville.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Neighbourhoods==\nOakville's Planning Department divides the town into communities.  These are based on traditional neighbourhoods.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/Offical_Plan_2006_consolidation.pdf|title=Town of Oakville Official Plan|date=2006-09-30|publisher=Town of Oakville|pages=130|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n[[File:Oakville Inn Hotel Sign.jpg|thumb|Oakville Inn Hotel sign]]\n[[File:Oakville Harbour.JPG|right|thumb|Oakville Harbour]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Neighbourhood!! Description\n|-\n| Old Oakville|| Old Oakville (downtown) is located in South-Central Oakville along the shore of [[Lake Ontario]], and is centred on Oakville Harbour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/OldOakville.pdf|title=Old Oakville Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n| Kerr Village|| Kerr Village is a section of downtown located just west of the Old Village around Kerr Street between Speers Rd and [[Lakeshore Road]].\n|-\n| Bronte|| [[Bronte, Ontario|Bronte]] is located in Southwest Oakville along the shore of Lake Ontario.  It is a community centred on Bronte Harbour and includes the Coronation Park district to its east.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/Bronte.pdf|title=Bronte Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n| Eastlake|| Eastlake is located in Southeast Oakville along the shore of Lake Ontario.  It is bordered on the west by Morrison Creek, to the north by Cornwall Road, and to the east by [[Mississauga]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/Eastlake.pdf|title=Eastlake Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|Clearview ||Clearview is located in Centre East Oakville. It is located on the Oakville-Mississauga border<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/Clearview.pdf|title=Clearview Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n| College Park|| College Park is located between [[Sixteen Mile Creek (Ontario)|Sixteen Mile Creek]] and just east of Trafalgar Road, from the [[Queen Elizabeth Way]] north to Upper Middle Road.  It surrounds Sheridan College.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/CollegePark.pdf|title=College Park Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n| Iroquois Ridge North||Iroquois Ridge North is located in North East Oakville between Upper Middle Road and Dundas Street.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/IRNorth.pdf|title=Iroquois Ridge North Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|Iroquois Ridge South ||Iroquois Ridge South is located in North East Oakville.  The Falgarwood area is located in the southern end of the Iroquois Ridge South community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/IRSouth.pdf|title=Iroquois Ridge South Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|Glen Abbey ||Glen Abbey is located in West Oakville, with Third Line being the major artery of the community.  It is a large area west of the [[Glen Abbey Golf Course]], home of the [[Canadian Open (golf)|Canadian Open]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/GlenAbbey.pdf|title=Glen Abbey Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|Palermo ||[[Palermo, Ontario|Palermo]] is located in Northwest Oakville.  It is a small community centred on the intersection of Dundas Street and Bronte Road (Highway 25).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/PalermoWest.pdf|title=Palermo Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|River Oaks ||River Oaks is located in North-Central Oakville.  It includes the Oak Park development.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/RiverOaks.pdf|title=River Oaks Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|Uptown Core ||Uptown Core is located in North Centre Oakville.  It includes the area on either side of Trafalgar Road between Dundas Street and Glenashton Drive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/UptownCore.pdf|title=Uptown Core Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|West Oak Trails ||West Oak Trails is located in North Centre West Oakville on the north side of Upper Middle Road.  It is a newer development than the other communities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/Media_Files/WestOakTrails.pdf|title=West Oak Trails Community Profile|year=2005|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|title       = Oakville\n|type        = Canada\n|align       = right\n|width       = \n|state       = \n|shading     = \n|percentages = \n|footnote    = \n|1841|550\n|1871|1684\n|1901|1643\n|1911|2372\n|1921|3298\n|1931|3857\n|1941|4115\n|1951|6910\n|1961|10366\n|1971|61483\n|1981|75773\n|1991|114670\n|[[Canada 1996 Census|1996]]|128405\n|[[Canada 2001 Census|2001]]|144738\n|[[Canada 2006 Census|2006]]|165613\n|[[Canada 2011 Census|2011]]|182520\n|[[Canada 2016 Census|2016]]|193832\n}}\n\nAccording to the 2016 Canadian Census, Oakville had 193,832 residents. This represents a 6.2% increase since the 2011 Census.<ref name=\"StatsCanProfile\" />\n\nAccording to the 2006 census, Oakville had a younger population than Canada as a whole. Minors (youth under 19 years of age) totalled 28.1 percent of the population compared to pensioners who number 11.7 percent. This compares with the Canadian average of 24.4 percent (minors) and 13.7 percent (pensioners).<ref name=\"CensusCommunity\">{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census06/data/profiles/community/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3524001&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Oakville&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=|title=Community highlights for Oakville|date=2008-04-30|work=2006 Census Data|publisher=Statistics Canada|accessdate=2008-06-04}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"right\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n!Ethnic Origin<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=FED&Code1=35060&Data=Count&SearchText=Oakville&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=Ethnic%20origin&B1=All&Custom=&amp;TABID=1|title= NHS Profile, Oakville, Ontario, 2011|date=2013-09-11|work=2011 Census Data|publisher=Statistics Canada|accessdate=2015-02-01}}</ref>\n!Population\n!Percent\n|-\n|[[English people|English]]\n|45,435\n|24.89%\n|-\n|[[Scottish people|Scottish]]\n|31,870\n|17.46%\n|-\n|[[Irish people|Irish]]\n|30,795\n|18.72%\n|-\n|[[Italian people|Italian]]\n|16,970\n|9.30%\n|-\n|[[German people|German]]\n|15,410\n|8.44%\n|-\n|[[French people|French]]\n|14,580\n|7.99%\n|-\n|[[Polish people|Polish]]\n|10,240\n|5.61%\n|-\n|[[Indo-Canadians|East Indian]]\n|9,605\n|5.26%\n|-\n|[[Chinese Canadian|Chinese]]\n|7,785\n|4.27%\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Canada 2016 Census!! Population !! % of Total Population\n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\" | [[Visible minority]] group<br><small>Source:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=1209034&Geo2=CD&Code2=1209&Data=Count&SearchText=Oakville&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1 |title=Community Profiles from the 2016 Census, Statistics Canada - Census Subdivision |publisher=2.statcan.gc.ca |date=December 6, 2010 |accessdate=April 13, 2013}}</ref></small> \n| [[South Asia]]n || 17,095 || {{Percentage | 17095 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n|| [[Chinese Canadian|Chinese]] || 13,435 || {{Percentage | 13435 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Arab Canadian|Arab]] || 6,095 || {{Percentage | 6095 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Black Canadians|Black]] || 5,520 || {{Percentage | 5520 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Filipino Canadian|Filipino]] || 3,710 || {{Percentage | 3710 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Latin American Canadian|Latin American]] || 3,595 || {{Percentage | 3595 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Korean Canadian|Korean]] || 3,080 || {{Percentage | 3080 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Western Asia|West Asian]] || 2,090 || {{Percentage | 2090 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Southeast Asia]]n || 1,030 || {{Percentage | 1030 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Japanese Canadians|Japanese]] || 690 || {{Percentage | 690 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| Other visible minority || 810 || {{Percentage | 810 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Multiracial|Mixed]] visible minority || 1,920 || {{Percentage | 1920 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | '''Total visible minority population'''|| '''59,075''' || '''{{Percentage | 59075 | 191720 | 1 }}'''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Aboriginal]] group<br><small>Source:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/hlt/97-558/pages/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo=CSD&Code=59&Table=1&Data=Count&Sex=1&Age=1&StartRec=26&Sort=2&Display=Page&CSDFilter=5000 |title=Aboriginal Peoples - Data table |publisher=2.statcan.ca |date=October 6, 2010|accessdate=April 13, 2013}}</ref></small> || [[First Nations]] || 810 || {{Percentage | 810 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[M\u00e9tis people (Canada)|M\u00e9tis]] || 560 || {{Percentage | 560 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Inuit]] || 0 || {{Percentage | 0 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | '''Total Aboriginal population''' || '''1,415''' || '''{{Percentage | 1415 | 191720 | 1 }}'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[European Canadian]] || 131,230 || {{Percentage | 131230 | 191720 | 1 }}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | '''''Total population''''' || '''''191,720''''' || '''''100%'''''\n|}\n\nAccording to the 2011 Census, 69.6% of Oakville residents have [[English language|English]] as their mother tongue (the corresponding figure for [[French language|French]] is 1.8%). [[Polish language|Polish]] is the native language for 1.5% of the population, followed by [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], and [[Spanish language|Spanish]] (at 1.4% each).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3524001&Geo2=CD&Code2=3524&Data=Count&SearchText=oakville&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1|title=Oakville, Ontario (Code 3524001) and Halton, Ontario (Code 3524) (table) Census Profile|last=Statistics Canada|date=24 October 2012|work=2011 Census|publisher=Statistics Canada Catalogue no. 98-316-XWE|location=Ottawa|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212192629/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3524001&Geo2=CD&Code2=3524&Data=Count&SearchText=oakville&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1|url-status=live|archivedate=12 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n79.4% of residents stated their religion as Christian, almost evenly split between Roman Catholics and Protestants. Non-Christian religions include [[Islam]]: 2.0%, [[Hinduism]]: 1.3%, [[Sikhism]]: 1.1%, and [[Judaism]]: 0.7%. 14% indicated no religion.\n\nThe median household income is $118, 671,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.halton.ca/cms/One.aspx?portalId=8310&pageId=109529|title=Median Household|publisher=halton.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> with an average house value of $1,118,572.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.omdreb.on.ca/news/market-watch|title=Average House Value|publisher=omdreb.on.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nThe top employers in Oakville include:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/assets/general%20-%20business/Top_100_Employers.pdf|title=Oakville Top 100 employers|publisher=oakville.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Company / organization'''\n! Employees\n! Sector\n|-\n| [[Halton Catholic District School Board]]||4,592||Education\n|-\n|[[Ford Motor Company of Canada]]||4,500||Head Office & Automobile Manufacturing Plant\n|-\n|[[Halton District School Board]]||2,393||Education\n|-\n|[[Halton Healthcare]]||2,290||Healthcare Services\n|-\n|[[Regional Municipality of Halton]]||2,054||Regional Government\n|-\n|[[Sheridan College]]||1,856||Post-Secondary Institution\n|-\n|The Corporation of the Town of Oakville||1,144||Municipal Government\n|-\n|}\n\n==Climate==\nLike much of Southern Ontario, Oakville has a humid continental climate with cold, but not extreme, winters and warm summers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.climate-data.org/location/47343/|title=Oakville Climate Data|publisher=climate-data.org|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n{{Oakville weatherbox}}\n\n==Sports==\n===Soccer===\nThe [[Oakville Blue Devils]] of [[League 1 Ontario]] is a professional soccer team. The Blue Devils are affiliated with the Oakville Soccer Club, which is the largest soccer club in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidehalton.com/sports-story/5799168-oakville-soccer-club-granted-membership-in-opdl|title=Oakville Soccer Club|publisher=insidehalton.com|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> Oakville boasts over 60 soccer fields and a Soccer Club Facility with a 2 star full size FIFA Certified indoor soccer pitch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakvillesoccer.ca/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=651:pine-glen-soccer-centre-corporate-rentals&catid=136:indoor-news&Itemid=71|title=Oakville Pine Glen Soccer Facility|publisher=oakvillesoccer.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Lacrosse===\nOakville is home to the headquarters and practice facilities of the [[Toronto Rock]] professional box lacrosse team competing in the National Lacrosse League. Oakville is also home to the 3rd largest minor lacrosse association in Ontario: The Oakville Minor Lacrosse Association has more than 1,500 players and competes in multiple classes and multiple divisions. The town also has the [[Oakville Buzz]], a [[OLA Junior A Lacrosse League|Junior \"A\"]] [[box lacrosse|lacrosse]] team who won the [[Founders Cup]] in 2006. The current rep lacrosse team is the Oakville Hawks.{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\n===Hockey===\n[[File:Sixteen Mile Sports Complex (NE View) - Oakville, ON.jpg|thumb|Oakville Blades home game]]\nThe [[Oakville Blades]] is a [[Ontario Provincial Junior A Hockey League|Tier II Junior \"A\"]] franchise since 1966, and a \"AAA\" hockey system. The current rep hockey team for boys  in Oakville is Oakville Rangers, who are the 2-time defending champions for the Midget \"AAA\" group. For girls, there is the Oakville Hornets, who are the largest female hockey association in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://moha.ca|title=Oakville Hockey|publisher=moha.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Skating===\nSkate Oakville, which is headquartered at Oakville's Sixteen Mile Creek Sports Complex, is the largest skating club in Canada,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidehalton.com/sports-story/4869180-skate-oakville-figure-skating-season-already-underway/|title=Oakville Figure Skating Season Underway|publisher=insidehalton.com|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> providing learn to skate lessons, recreational figure skating programs, competitive training, and 10 synchronized skating teams.<ref>{{cite web|title=Skate Oakville|url=https://www.skateoakville.ca/|website=Skate Oakville.ca|publisher=Skate Oakville|accessdate=2015-11-03}}</ref>\n\n===Baseball===\nBaseball is represented in Oakville by two organizations, Oakville Little League and the OMBA (Oakville Minor Baseball Association).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.insidehalton.com/sports-story/4497626-oakville-baseball-associations-to-open-2014-seasons-next-saturday|title=Oakville Basketball associations to Open|publisher=insidehalton.com|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOakville Little League is the largest [[Little League Baseball|Little League]] organization in Canada. In 2018, there were over 1,150 young people playing across eight divisions and over 90 teams, including 7 All-Star teams. Oakville Little League also fields six All-Star (Rep) teams, known as the Oakville Whitecaps. The 12U and 14U Whitecaps teams compete annually to play in the [[Little League World Series]] and [[Junior League World Series]], respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehalton.com/community-story/5803168-junior-world-series-everything-and-more-for-oakville-whitecaps/|title=Junior World Series 'everything, and more' for Oakville Whitecaps|publisher=insidehalton.com|accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe OMBA (Oakville Minor Baseball Association) was established in 1963.  It offers 3 levels of baseball to children and youth in Oakville:  House League, Select and Rep.  OMBA runs the Oakville A's, the official Town Rep baseball playing in the Central Ontario Baseball Association (COBA) system.\n===Golf===\n[[Glen Abbey Golf Course]], site of several [[Canadian Open (golf)|Canadian Open]] professional golf championships and many other amateur tournaments, is also located in Oakville.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2018/11/08/fight-for-oakvilles-glen-abbey-golf-course-heading-to-ontario-court-of-appeal.html |title=Fight for Oakville\u2019s Glen Abbey Golf Course heading to Ontario Court of Appeal |date=8 November 2018 |website=Toronto Start |publisher=Metroland News |access-date=8 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Canoeing===\nAnother sport Oakville is well known for is its [[Burloak Canoe Club]], where they have had Olympians come out of, such as [[Adam van Koeverden]], [[Mark Oldershaw]] and [[Larry Cain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://burloakcanoe.com/about-us/wall-of-fame/|title=Burloak Canoe|publisher=burloakcanoe.com|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n\n===Downtown Oakville Jazz Festival===\nThe [[Downtown Oakville Jazz Festival]] is an annual summer jazz festival, since 1992.  The event includes performances at a number of stages along [[Lakeshore Road]] in downtown Oakville.  The event is free to the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://visitoakville.com/events/downtown-oakville-jazz-festival/|title=Visit Oakville|publisher=City Of Oakville|accessdate=Aug 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Waterfront Festival===\nBeginning in 1982, Oakville's Coronation Park played host to the annual [[Oakville Waterfront Festival]].  Among a range of events, the festival included small amusement park rides, arts and crafts, food and drinks, free concerts headlined by Canadian bands, and nightly fireworks displays.  The Waterfront Festival took place in late June of each year until 2010, when it was cancelled due to financial difficulties,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidehalton.com/news/article/437645|title=Plug pulled on Oakville Waterfront Festival|publisher=InsideHalton|date=2009-12-03}}</ref> despite having annual attendance of up to 100,000 visitors. It returned in August 2013,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lea|first=David|title=Oakville's Waterfront Festival returning in August|url=http://www.insidehalton.com/news/article/1589407--oakville-s-waterfront-festival-returning-in-august|work=insidehalton.com|accessdate=23 April 2013}}</ref> which was the final festival to date.\n\n===Kerrfest===\nThe Kerrfest is an annual outdoor music festival that takes place in early September in Oakville. Having begun in 2014, the event includes free performances and is open to the public, located at Westwood Park.<ref>https://www.inhalton.com/everything-you-need-to-know-about-kerrfest-in-oakville-this-weekend</ref>\n\n===For the Love of the Arts Festival===\nThe For the Love of the Arts Festival is an annual event taking place in the late spring in Oakville. Inaugurated in 2002, the event is hosted by CommUnity Arts Space (originally known as Music and Art Shared Space who initiated the festival), a local umbrella group advocating for shared physical space for Oakville's arts and cultural groups.<ref>{{cite web|title=In Ontario: Oakville Music And Art Shared Space|url=http://www.inontario.ca/ArtsEntertainment/OakvilleMusicArt/tabid/178/Default.aspx|website=In Ontario}}</ref>  Currently the only such multi-disciplinary community festival of its kind in Oakville, the event serves to showcase local talent, skills, crafts, literary art, dance performances, theatre groups and music performances.  The event is intended as a symbolic presentation of a \"shared space\" and is entirely sponsored by local corporate and private donations.<ref>{{cite web|title=For Love Of The Arts Festival|url=https://oakville.snapd.com/event/168969#/|website=Snapd Oakville|accessdate=Aug 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Canadian Open===\nThe [[Glen Abbey Golf Course]] is the home to the [[Golf Canada]] and the [[Canadian Golf Hall of Fame]].  It has hosted 31 [[Canadian Open (golf)|Canadian Open]] Championships since 1977, most recently in July 2018. Glen Abbey is owned by [[Clublink]], which was planning to demolish the golf course in order to build residential and commercial units, if it is successful in overturning the city's decision to prevent the development. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/golf/2018/07/20/this-year-could-be-glen-abbeys-last-as-owners-plan-redevelopment-for-condos-and-offices.html |title=This year could be Glen Abbey\u2019s last as owners plan redevelopment for condos and offices |date=20 July 2018 |website=Toronto Start |publisher=Metroland News |access-date=27 October 2018}}</ref>  In 2018, the company achieved some success in its efforts against the town, after a Superior Court ruled against the town's attempts to block the redevelopment. The Local Planning Appeal Tribunal (LPAT) will hold two hearing in 2019 on ClubLink\u2019s appeal of the town's decision. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/9080143-town-of-oakville-dealt-another-courtroom-setback-in-fight-to-save-glen-abbey-golf-course/ |title=Town of Oakville dealt another courtroom setback in fight to save Glen Abbey Golf Course |date=12 December 2018 |website=Inside Halton |publisher=Metroland News |access-date=15 December 2018|quote=Conservation plan and related bylaws struck down by Ontario Superior Court of Justice}}</ref>\n\nThe 2019 and 2023 events were scheduled to be held at the Hamilton Golf and Country Club but the Canadian Open may again be held at Glen Abbey in some future years if the redevelopment is not allowed to proceed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/golf/hamilton-to-host-canadian-open-in-2019-2023-1.4694543|title=Canadian Open returning to Hamilton in 2019, 2023 |date=6 June 2018 |publisher=CBC Sports |access-date=15 December 2018|quote=Applebaum said Golf Canada has not ruled out returning to Glen Abbey in the future but is \"speaking with a variety of people\" about hosting 2020, 2021, and 2022.}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n{{see also|List of schools in Oakville, Ontario}}\n\nElementary schools and high schools in Oakville are a mix of private and public schools, with one of the highest ratios of private schools to student population in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.robkelly.ca/Our-Communities---Oakville.html|title=Oakville School Communities|publisher=robkelley.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> Oakville is covered by the [[Halton District School Board]], [[Halton Catholic District School Board]], [[Conseil scolaire Viamonde]], and [[Conseil scolaire catholique MonAvenir]]. [[St. Thomas Aquinas Catholic Secondary School (Oakville)]] and [[White Oaks Secondary School]] both offer the [[International Baccalaureate]] Program.\n\nThe town is home to [[Appleby College]], a private school for grades seven to twelve, established in 1911<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.appleby.on.ca|title=Appleby Website|publisher=appleby.on.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> as well as [[St. Mildred's-Lightbourn School]], an independent all-girls school. Oakville is also home to the Trafalgar Campus of [[Sheridan College]], primarily an arts and business studies institute, and Oakville's only higher education facility.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sheridancollege.ca|title=Sheridan College Website|publisher=sheridancollege.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\n\n===Municipal and regional===\nAt the municipal level, the governing body is the [[Oakville Town Council]] consisting of a [[List of mayors of Oakville, Ontario|mayor]] (currently [[Rob Burton]]) and fourteen [[councillors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.hipinfo.info/record/OAK1575|title=Members of Oakville Town Council|publisher=search.hipinfp.info|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>  The town is divided into seven [[Ward (politics)|wards]], with two councillors elected by residents of each ward.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/assets/general%20-%20town%20hall/WBR-ASC-11nov15.pdf|title=Oakville Ward Review|publisher=oakville.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn each ward one councillor represents the ward solely on Oakville Town Council, and the other is a member of the 21-member governing council of the [[Regional Municipality of Halton]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/assets/general%20-%20town%20hall/WBR-ASC-11nov15.pdf|title=Oakville Governing Council|publisher=oakville.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> in addition to being a member of the 13-member Town Council.\n\n===Provincial===\nOakville is situated in two provincial [[Electoral district (Canada)|ridings]] which use the same boundaries as the federal ridings and are currently represented provincially by:\n\n* [[Oakville (provincial electoral district)|Oakville]]: [[Stephen Crawford (politician)|Stephen Crawford]] ([[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|Conservative]])<ref name=\"Who are the Halton winners? All PC\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/8658442-who-are-the-halton-winners-all-pc/|title=Who are the Halton winners? All PC|date=2018-06-07|work=InsideHalton.com|access-date=2018-07-14|language=en-CA}}</ref>\n*[[Oakville North\u2014Burlington (provincial electoral district)|Oakville North-Burlington]]: [[Effie Triantafilopoulos]] ([[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|Conservative]])<ref name=\"Who are the Halton winners? All PC\"/>\n\n===Federal===\nOakville is situated in two federal [[Electoral district (Canada)|ridings]] which are currently represented by:\n\n* [[Oakville (electoral district)|Oakville]]: [[Anita Anand (professor)|Anita Anand]] ([[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]])<ref>https://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/9655754--collective-victory-liberal-anita-anand-is-the-oakville-riding-s-new-mp/</ref>\n* [[Oakville North\u2014Burlington|Oakville North-Burlington]]: [[Pam Damoff]] ([[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/5968252-updated-liberal-pam-damoff-takes-new-oakville-north-burlington-mp-seat/|title=Liberal Pam Damoff takes new Oakville North\u2014Burlington MP seat|last=Le|first=Julia|date=20 October 2015|work=Oakville Beaver|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029070812/http://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/5968252-updated-liberal-pam-damoff-takes-new-oakville-north-burlington-mp-seat/|url-status=live|archivedate=29 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Arts and culture==\n===Oakville Centre for the Performing Arts===\n[[Image:Oakville-Centre-for-Performing-Arts.JPG|thumb|right|Oakville Centre for the Performing Arts]]The [[Oakville Centre for the Performing Arts]] houses several performances by local and international artists. It is also the performing venue for the [[Oakville Symphony Orchestra]], the [[Oakville Children's Choir]] and the [[Oakville Ballet Company]]. The Oakville Arts Council provides further artistic talents in the town showcasing films, literary figures and visual arts.\n\n===The Oakville Children's Choir===\nThe [[Oakville Children's Choir]] has been in business since 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehalton.com/whatson-story/5640147-oakville-children-s-choir-ends-season-with-concert-award/|title=Oakville Children's Choir wins awards|publisher=insidehalton.com|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Oakville Galleries ===\nOakville Galleries is a not-for-profit art museum that exhibits contemporary art, cares for a permanent collection and delivers public programming. Its exhibition spaces are located on two sites: Gairloch Gardens and Centennial Square.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oakvillegalleries.com/about/mission|title=Gallery website|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n==Media==\nOakville is primarily served by media based in Toronto with markets in the [[Greater Toronto Area]] (GTA) that cover most of the news in the GTA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/townhall/nr-17feb03.html|title=Oakville GTA|publisher=oakville.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> One regional newspaper, the ''[[Oakville Beaver]]'', is published once weekly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://search.hipinfo.info/record/OAK1249|title=Oakville Beaver|website=search.hipinfo.info|access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehalton.com/oakville-on/|title=Oakville Beaver|publisher=insidehalton.com|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\nThe monthly magazines Neighbours of Joshua Creek, Neighbours of Glen Abbey and Neighbours of Olde Oakville serve three key neighbourhoods.\n\nThe town also has two specialty radio stations: AM 1250 [[CJYE]], a [[Christian music]] station<ref>{{cite web|url=https://radio-locator.com/info/CJYE-AM|title=AM 1250 Radio Locator|publisher=radio-locator.com|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> and AM 1320 [[CJMR]], a [[Multiculturalism|Multicultural]] station.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tunein.com/radio/CJMR-1320-s31220/|title=AM 1320 Radio Tune In|publisher=tunein.com|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe following national cable television station also broadcast from Oakville:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yellowpages.ca/search/si/1/Television+Stations+%26+Broadcasting+Companies/Oakville+ON|title=Television Broadcasting from Oakville|publisher=yellowpages.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n*[[The Weather Network]] has broadcast nationally from Oakville since 2005\n* The Hamilton-based television station [[CHCH-DT]] serves [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]], [[Halton Region, Ontario|Halton]] and [[Niagara Region, Ontario|Niagara]], thus including Oakville. CHCH recently closed its Halton Bureau (due to budget considerations) which was located in downtown Oakville.\n*[[TVCogeco]] from the studio in the [[Cogeco Cable]] Headquarters at Harvester Road & Burloak Drive, just inside of [[Burlington, Ontario|Burlington]].\n\n==Transportation==\n[[Oakville Transit]] provides local bus service. [[GO Transit]] commuter rail and bus service operates from [[Bronte GO Station|Bronte]] and [[Oakville GO Station|Oakville]] stations. [[Via Rail]] services along the line between [[Quebec City \u2013 Windsor Corridor|Windsor and Quebec corridor]], and operates from Oakville station.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.viarail.ca/en/travel-info/transport-services/intermodality/go-transit|title=Oakville Transportation Info|publisher=viarail.ca|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Queen Elizabeth Way]], [[Ontario Highway 403]], and the [[407 ETR]] highways run through Oakville.\n\n==Emergency services==\n[[Policing]] in Oakville is performed by the [[Halton Regional Police Service]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrps.on.ca/Locations/Oakville/pages/default.aspx|title=Oakville|work=Halton Region Police Service|publisher=Regional Municipality of Halton Police Services Board|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304114134/http://www.hrps.on.ca/Locations/Oakville/Pages/default.aspx|url-status=dead|archivedate=4 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Fire service]] is provided by the town through the Oakville Fire Department with eight [[fire station]]s.\n\nThe Town of Oakville's Waters Air Rescue Force (TOWARF) is a volunteer organization that provides marine search and rescue service in Western Lake Ontario. It was founded in 1954 and was a charter member of the [[Canadian Coast Guard Auxiliary]].<ref name=towarf>{{cite web|title=TOWARF|url=http://www.towarf.com/|work=TOWARF \u2013 Town of Oakville Water Air Rescue Force|accessdate=2011-02-26}}</ref>\n\n==Commerce==\n[[File:Tim Hortons corporate headquarters - 01.jpg|thumb|[[Tim Hortons]] headquarters]]\n\n===Employers===\n\n[[Tim Hortons]] (moving to Toronto)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/real_estate/2018/04/17/tim-hortons-to-move-its-canadian-head-office.html|title=Tim Hortons to move its Canadian head office {{!}} The Star|work=thestar.com|access-date=2018-07-14|language=en}}</ref> and [[Mattamy Homes]] are based in Oakville while [[Siemens]], [[Ford Motor Company of Canada|The Ford Motor Company,]] and MADD Canada have their head Canadian offices in the town. Many Oakville residents work in advanced manufacturing at large facilities operated by [[UTC Aerospace Systems]] and [[General Electric]].<ref name=\"Top Employers By Sector\">{{cite web|title=Top Employers By Sector|url=http://www.oakville.ca/economicdevelopment/top-employers.html|website=oakville.ca|publisher=City Of Oakville|accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nMany Oakville companies fall under the [[List of life sciences|life science umbrella]], with an emphasis on [[Pharmaceutical industry|pharmaceuticals]] and [[elder care]].<ref name=\"Top Employers By Sector\" /> There are also a number of retirement homes in the city.<ref name=\"Top Employers By Sector\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Retirement Homes Oakville|url=http://www.comfortlife.ca/retirement-communities/oakville-retirement-homes|website=Comfort Life|publisher=Our Kids Media|accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs Oakville is considered part of the [[Greater Toronto Area]] it is common for residents to commute to jobs in [[Toronto]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Living In Toronto What's It Like|url=http://www.livingin-canada.com/living-in-toronto.html|website=Living In Canada|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Oakville Place===\nThe Oakville Place Shopping Centre is an indoor shopping mall in Oakville that opened in 1981.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.eyeonsheridan.com/oakville-place-is-the-place-to-be/|last= Kukolic|first= Kristina|title= Oakville Place Is The Place To Be|publisher= Eye on Sheridan|date= 2010-12-09|accessdate= 2015-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= http://www.bramptonguardian.com/news-story/3910504-ceiling-collapses-at-oakville-place/ |title= Ceiling collapses at The Bay in Oakville Place|last= Lea|first= David|newspaper= Oakville Beaver|date= 2013-07-25|accessdate= 2015-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= http://thesheridansun.ca/blog/2014/03/24/oakville-place-is-just-dancing-this-march-break/ |newspaper= The Sheridan Sun|title= Oakville Place is Just Dancing this March Break|last= Paisley|first= Dylan|date= 2014-03-24|accessdate= 2015-05-25}}</ref>  The mall is approximately {{convert|42000|m2|sqft|-3}}.<ref name = \"Maitland1990\">{{cite book | first= Barry |last= Maitland | title = The new architecture of the retail mall | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Cg9UAAAAMAAJ | accessdate = 2014-06-19 | year = 1990 | location= New York|publisher = Van Nostrand Reinhold|isbn= 9781854548153|oclc= 23726658}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=tA1UAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Oakville+Place%22&dq=%22Oakville+Place%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=lemfU6jsOsLZoAT43YKoCA&ved=0CCMQ6AEwAjgU |title= Shopping malls: planning and design|first= Barry|last= Maitland|year= 1985|location= New York|publisher= Nichols|page= 173|isbn= 9780893972264|oclc= 11971331}}</ref>\n\n===Smart Centre Oakville===\nSmart Centre Oakville is a retail mall located in the northeast end of Oakville.\n\n==Sister cities==\nOakville is twinned with the cities of [[Dorval]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/454427461.html?dids=454427461:454427461&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=May+28%2C+1992&author=Bobbi-Jean+MacKinnon+Toronto+Star&pub=Toronto+Star&desc=People-to-people+appeal+for+Canada+growing&pqatl=google|title=People-to-people appeal for Canada growing|last=MacKinnon|first=Bobbi-Jean|date=1992-05-28|work=Toronto Star|page=MA.6|accessdate=2009-08-28}}</ref> in Quebec, and [[Neyagawa]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oakville.ca/sistercity.htm|title=Oakville's Sister City \u2013 Neyagawa, Japan|work=Oakville.ca|publisher=Town of Oakville|accessdate=2009-08-28|archivedate=2009-08-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814030530/http://www.oakville.ca/sistercity.htm}}</ref> Japan. The Town of Oakville has named two major streets after these cities.  In 2015, [[Huai'an]], China became a sister city to Oakville.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Town of Oakville forms sister city bond with Huai\u2019an, China|publisher=Town of Oakville|date=24 Aug 2015|url=https://www.oakville.ca/townhall/nr-15aug24.html|accessdate=1 August 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628064647/https://www.oakville.ca/townhall/nr-15aug24.html|archivedate=28 Jun 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Ontario}}\n* [[:Category:People from Oakville, Ontario]]\n* [[List of people from Oakville, Ontario]]\n* [[List of schools in Oakville, Ontario]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Oakville}}\n{{wikivoyage|Oakville (Ontario)|Oakville, Ontario}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.oakville.ca/ }}\n\n{{Geographic location|\nNorthwest=[[Milton, Ontario|Milton]]|\nSouthwest=[[Burlington, Ontario|Burlington]]|\nCenter=Oakville|\nNortheast=[[Mississauga]]|\nSoutheast=''[[Lake Ontario]]''|}}\n\n{{Oakville, Ontario}}\n{{Halton region}}\n{{Greater Toronto Area}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Lower-tier municipalities in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Oakville, Ontario| ]]\n[[Category:Populated places on Lake Ontario in Canada]]\n[[Category:1827 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Underground Railroad]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1827]]\n", "name_user": "174.138.203.21", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Some brief informative facts about Oakville)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oakville,_Ontario"}
{"title_page": "Joy (singer)", "text_new": "{{for|the Australian singer|Joy (Australian musician)}}\n{{short description|South Korean singer and actress}}\n{{Korean name |Park}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Joy\n| image              = 20191002 \uc870\uc774.png<!-- Please do NOT change the image unless you have compelling reason for doing so. If there's really such reason, please include in edit summary. Thank you. -->\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Joy in October 2019\n| native_name        = \ubc15\uc218\uc601<ref name=birth>[http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=004&oid=366&aid=0000289511 \"\uc6b0\ub9ac\uacb0\ud63c\ud588\uc5b4\uc694, \uc0ac\ub791\uc2a4\ub7ec\uc6b4 '\uc870\uc774'\uc758 \ubcf8\uba85\uc740 \uc5bc\ub9c8\ub098 \uc608\uc060\uae4c?] ''Naver News'', September 12, 2015. Retrieved December 20, 2015.</ref>\n| birth_name         = Park Soo-young<ref name=birth/>\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1996|9|3}}\n| birth_place        = [[Jeju Island]], South Korea\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer|actress}}\n| signature          = \n| signature_size     = \n| signature_alt      = \n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background        = solo_singer\n| genre             = {{hlist|[[K-pop]]}}\n| instrument        = Vocals\n| years_active      = 2014\u2013present\n| label             = [[SM Entertainment|SM]]\n| associated_acts   = {{hlist|[[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]]|[[SM Town]]}}\n| module = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes\n| title  = [[Korean name]]\n| hangul = {{linktext|\ubc15|\uc218|\uc601}}\n| hanja  =  {{linktext|\u6734|\u79c0|\u82f1}}<ref name=profile>Seong Jin Hee. [http://thestar.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2014/09/26/2014092601405.html \ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3 \uc870\uc774 \"\uc2ac\uae30\uc640 \ud55c \ubc29 \uc4f0\uace0 \uc2f6\uc740 \uc774\uc720? \uc7a0\ub4e4\uba74 \uc808\ub300 \uc548 \uae68\"] ''The Star'', September 26, 2014. Retrieved September 26, 2014.</ref><ref>Kwon Soo Bin. [http://news1.kr/articles/?2366836 '\uc6b0\uacb0' \uc721\uc131\uc7ac, \uc870\uc774 \uc2e0\ubd84\uc99d \uc0ac\uc9c4\uc5d0 \"\uc608\uc058\ub2e4, \uc544\ub098\uc6b4\uc11c \uac19\uc544\"] ''News 1'', August 8, 2015. Retrieved August 8, 2015.JOY</ref>\n| rr          = Bak Su-yeong\n| mr          = Pak Suy\u014fng\n| hangulstage = {{linktext|\uc870|\uc774}}\n| rrstage     = Jo-I\n| mrstage     = Ch'oI\n}}}}\n}}\n\n'''Park Soo-young''' (born September 3, 1996),<ref name=birth/><ref name=smprofile>[http://redvelvet.smtown.com/profile Red Velvet Profile] Retrieved October 11, 2014.</ref> known by the stage name '''Joy''', is a South Korean singer, actress and television host. She is a member of the South Korean girl group [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]]. Aside from group activities, Joy has had starring roles in  [[Korean drama|television dramas]], [[The Liar and His Lover (TV series)|''The Liar and His Lover'']] (2017) and [[Tempted (TV series)|''Tempted'']] (2018).\n\n== Early life ==\nPark Soo-young was born in [[Jeju Island]] and raised in [[Dobong District]], [[Seoul]]. Her family consists of her parents and two younger sisters, Park Ji-yeong and Park Min-ji.<ref name=\"profile\" />\n\nAs a child, Joy was interested in modern [[trot music]] and was influenced to become a singer after receiving praise for her rendition of [[Korean rock]] band [[Cherry Filter]]'s song ''Flying Duck'' during a grade school festival.<ref>[http://www.enewstoday.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=378785 \ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3, '\uc544\uc774\uc2a4\ud06c\ub9bcTV' \ubc29\uc1a1 \uc55e\ub450\uace0 \ube44\uae00\u7f8e \ubc1c\uc0b0\u2026 '\uac1c\uc778\uae30 \ub300\ubc29\ucd9c'] ''E News Today'', March 30, 2015. Retrieved January 8, 2016.</ref><ref>Kwon Soo Bin. [http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=421&aid=0000990161 \ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3, \ubcfc\uc218\ub85d \ud589\ubcf5\ud574\uc9c0\ub294 \uc18c\ub140\ub4e4(\uc778\ud130\ubdf0)] ''News 1'',  September 1, 2014. Retrieved March 10,2015.</ref><ref>[http://ssulf.com/bbs/board.php?bo_table=funny&wr_id=111873 \ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3 \uc870\uc774 \uc911\ud559\uad50 \ub54c '\uc624\ub9ac\ub0a0\ub2e4'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104091715/http://ssulf.com/bbs/board.php?bo_table=funny&wr_id=111873|date=2017-01-04}} ''Ssulf'', Retrieved January 3, 2017.</ref> Joy auditioned and was cast by [[SM Entertainment]] at the SM Global Audition in Seoul in 2012. She trained under the agency for two years, during which time a vocal coach gave her the stage name \"Joy\".<ref name=\"birth\" />\n\n== Life and career ==\n===1996\u20132014: Career beginnings===\n{{see also|Red Velvet (group)}}Joy was introduced as the fourth member of [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]] on July 29, 2014.<ref>Hwang Mi-hyeon. [http://osen.mt.co.kr/article/G1109914877 SM, \uc5d1\uc18c \uc774\ud6c4 2\ub144\ub9cc\uc758 \uc2e0\uc778..\uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 '\ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3' \uacf5\uac1c] ''OSEN'', July 28, 2014. Retrieved February 11, 2017.</ref><ref>Choi Jin-sil. [http://tenasia.hankyung.com/archives/290192 \ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3, 8\uc6d4 1\uc77c \u2018\ubba4\uc9c1\ubc45\ud06c\u2019\uc11c \ub300\ub9dd\uc758 \ub370\ubdd4 \ubb34\ub300] ''Ten Asia'', July 30, 2014. Retrieved February 11, 2017.</ref> She is the only member of the group who was not introduced as a part of [[SM Rookies]] before the group's debut. The group made their music debut with the [[digital single]] \"Happiness\" on August 1, 2014<ref>Ock Hyun-ju [http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20140730000536 SM's Red Velvet to stage debut Aug. 1] ''[[The Korea Herald]]'', July 30, 2014. Retrieved August 1, 2014.</ref> and became the first K-pop girl group to send their debut single to the [[Billboard charts]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8496164/cherry-bullet-qna-debut-single-world-digital-song-sales-chart|title=Debut on World Digital Song Sales Chart With 'Q&A'|last=|first=|date=|website=Billboard|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref> Since 2014, Red Velvet has released eleven [[Extended play|EP]]<nowiki/>s and two [[studio albums]] and has become regarded by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' and ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' as one of the most popular [[K-pop]] groups worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/8544710/best-k-pop-songs-2010s-top-100|title=The 100 Greatest K-Pop Songs of the 2010s: Staff List|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n===2015\u2013present: Solo activities===\nIn 2015, Joy joined the [[We Got Married (Season 4)|fourth season]] of [[MBC TV|MBC]] variety show ''[[We Got Married]]'', where she appeared opposite [[BtoB (band)|BtoB]] member [[Yook Sungjae|Yook Sung-jae]].<ref name=\"wgm\">{{cite web|author=Grace Danbi Hong|url=http://mwave.interest.me/en/kpop-news/article/93524/red-velvet-joy-revealed-as-btob-yook-sung-jaes-we-got-married-partner|title=Red Velvet Joy Revealed as BTOB Yook Sung Jae\u2032s \u2032We Got Married\u2032 Partner|publisher=MWave|date=June 3, 2015|accessdate=August 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212091553/http://mwave.interest.me/en/kpop-news/article/93524/red-velvet-joy-revealed-as-btob-yook-sung-jaes-we-got-married-partner|archive-date=February 12, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> She received significant recognition for her participation in the TV program and featured in her first solo pictorial in Korean fashion magazine ''C\u00e9Ci'', concurrent to modeling for [[Etude House]] cosmetics.<ref>Kim A-reum. [http://news.newsway.co.kr/view.php?tp=1&ud=2015092417034212705&md=20150924172403_AO \ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3 \uc870\uc774, \uc0ac\ub791\uc2a4\ub7ec\uc6b4 \ub9e4\ub825 \ub4ec\ubfcd \ub2f4\uae34 \ud654\ubcf4 \uacf5\uac1c] ''News Way'', September 24, 2015. Retrieved February 11, 2017.</ref> On December 29, 2015, Joy won the New Star Award and the Best Couple Award at the [[MBC Entertainment Awards|2015 MBC Entertainment Awards]].<ref>Choi Min-ji. [http://chicnewsm.mk.co.kr/article.php?aid=145139435588323006#_adinctep MBC\uc5f0\uc608\ub300\uc0c12015 \uc870\uc774 \ub274\uc2a4\ud0c0\uc0c1 \ubc1b\uace0 \uc721\uc131\uc7ac\uc5d0\uac8c \"\uc624\ube60 \ub098 \uc0c1 \ubc1b\uc558\uc5b4\"] ''Chic News'', December 29, 2015. Retrieved December 30, 2015.</ref> Joy also released a duet with Yook on April 16, 2016 entitled \"Young Love\" that reached #1 on [[KT Corporation|Genie]], with Joy receiving official songwriting credit from [[Korea Music Copyright Association|KOMCA]] for contributing to its lyrical composition.<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.melon.com/song/detail.htm?songId=8147756|title=Young Love Song Credits \uc5b4\ub9b0\uc560(\u611b)|website=Melon|language=ko|access-date=2019-01-06}}</ref> Departing from ''[[We Got Married]]'' on May 7, 2016 they became known as one of the longest-running and most popular couples in the show's history.<ref>Jeong Yuna. [http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=076&aid=0002928633 '\uc6b0\uacb04' \uc721\uc131\uc7ac\uc870\uc774, \uc544\uc8fc \ud2b9\ubcc4\ud55c \uc774\ubcc4 \ucf58\uc11c\ud2b8] ''Naver'', May 7, 2016. Retrieved May 7, 2016.</ref><ref>Park So-hyun. [http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=311&aid=0000605199 '\uc6b0\uacb0' \uc721\uc131\uc7ac\uc870\uc774, \ub208\ubb3c\ub85c 11\uac1c\uc6d4 \ub9c8\ubb34\ub9ac \"\uc03c \uc548\ub155\"] ''Naver'', May 7, 2016. Retrieved May 7, 2016.</ref><ref>Jeong Hee-yeon. [http://entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=382&aid=0000471597 \u2018\uc6b0\uacb0\u2019 \uc03c\ucee4\ud50c \uc870\uc774-\uc721\uc131\uc7ac, \uc774\ubcc4 \uc55e\ub450\uace0 \ud3ed\ud0c4 \uace0\ubc31] ''Naver'', May 6, 2016. Retrieved May 7, 2016.</ref>[[File:171202 \uba5c\ub860 \ubba4\uc9c1 \uc5b4\uc6cc\uc988 \ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3 (3).jpg|thumb|238x238px|Joy during [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]]'s performance at the 2017 [[Melon Music Awards|MMA]]|alt=|left]] \n\nIn November 2016, Joy collaborated with [[Lim Seul-ong]] in a duet titled \"Always In My Heart\".<ref>Seon Mi-kyeong. [http://entertain.naver.com/topic/999390/999390/read?oid=109&aid=0003426374 \uc784\uc2ac\uc639\u2665\uc870\uc774, \uc560\ud2cb\ud558\uac8c \uc0ac\ub791\uc2a4\ub7f0 \ucf00\ubbf8..'\uc774\ubcc4\uc744 \ubc30\uc6e0\uc5b4'] ''OSEN'', November 4, 2016. Retrieved November 4, 2016.</ref><ref>Hwang Su-yeon. [http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=201611041308187423666_1 \ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3 \uc870\uc774, \ub4c0\uc5e3\uc7a5\uc778 \uc784\uc2ac\uc639\uc744 \ub9cc\ub098\ub2e4] ''Herald Pop'', November 4, 2016. Retrieved February 11, 2017.</ref> The song achieved an overall ranking of #2 on the Instiz iChart,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/instiz_ichart/status/795317625353945088|title=Instiz iChart\u2122|last=iChart\u2122|date=2016-11-06|website=@instiz_ichart|language=ko|access-date=2018-12-18}}</ref> reached #1 on [[KT Corporation|Genie]], [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]], [[Soribada]], Olleh, and Monkey3, #2 on Bugs,<ref>[https://twitter.com/instiz_ichart/status/795332728354848768 Always In My Heart at #2] ''Instiz'', November 7, 2016. Retrieved November 19, 2016.</ref> debuted at #10 on [[Melon (online music service)|Melon]], and peaked at #7 on the [[Gaon Digital Chart|Gaon]] Download Chart and #10 on the [[Gaon Digital Chart|Gaon]] Digital Chart.<ref>[http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=S1020&targetTime=46&hitYear=2016&termGbn=week http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2016&targetTime=46&nationGbn=T] Retrieved November 19, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Joy made her acting debut as the female lead in [[TVN (South Korea)|tvN]]'s music drama ''[[The Liar and His Lover (TV series)|The Liar and His Lover]]''.<ref>Park So-hyun. [http://m.entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=311&aid=0000693327 \ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3 \uc870\uc774, \uc5f0\uae30\ub3cc \ubcc0\uc2e0\u2026SM \uce21 \"'\uadf8\ub140\ub294 \uac70\uc9d3\ub9d0~' \ucd9c\uc5f0 \ud655\uc815] ''Xports News'', January 13, 2017. Retrieved January 13, 2017.</ref><ref name=\"tlah12\">{{Cite news|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201701131720461185332_2|title=Lee Hyun-woo, Red Velvet's Joy to star in 'She Loves Lie So Much'|date=January 13, 2017|work=Kpop Herald|access-date=}}</ref> It is the Korean television adaptation of [[Kotomi Aoki]]'s popular [[manga]] ''[[Kanojo wa Uso o Aishisugiteru]]''.<ref name=\"tlahl2\">Ambili S. [http://www.ibtimes.sg/red-velvets-joy-make-acting-debut-tvn-drama-6796 Red Velvet's Joy to make acting debut in tvN drama] ''[[International Business Times]]'', January 24, 2017. Retrieved January 26, 2017.</ref><ref>Baek Sol Mi. [http://sports.donga.com/3/all/20161216/81881713/1 \u2018\uadf8\ub140\ub294 \uac70\uc9d3\ub9d0\uc744 \ub108\ubb34 \uc0ac\ub791\ud574\u2019, \uac00\ucc3d\ub825\uc758 \uc8fc\uc778\uacf5\uc744 \ucc3e\uc544\ub77c] ''Sports Donga'', December 17, 2016. Retrieved February 11, 2017.</ref> Joy won the Newcomer Award at the OSEN Cable TV Awards for her first acting role, and released several OSTs for the drama including ''Yeowooya'', ''I'm Okay'', ''Your Days'', ''Shiny Boy'', ''Waiting For You'', and ''The Way To Me''.<ref name=\"osen\">[http://www.stardailynews.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=216732 <nowiki>[61]</nowiki>]</ref> In July 2017, Joy appeared on ''[[King of Mask Singer]]'' where she won her first round of the singing competition program and performed under the alias of ''Bandabi''.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2018, Joy joined the second season of JTBC music variety show ''[[Two Yoo Project Sugar Man|Sugar Man]]'' as a co-host alongside [[Yoo Jae-suk]], [[You Hee-yeol]], and [[Park Na-rae (comedian)|Park Na-rae]].<ref name=sms2>{{Cite news|author=Kang Seojeong|title=\ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3 \uc870\uc774X\ubc15\ub098\ub798, '\uc288\uac00\ub9e82' \ud569\ub958\ud655\uc815..\ud22c\uc720\uc640 \ud638\ud761|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0003678440|work=OSEN|date=December 11, 2017|accessdate=December 13, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, Joy was also cast as the female lead in the [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]] drama'' [[Tempted (TV series)|Tempted]]'', loosely based on the French novel ''Les Liaisons dangereuses''.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Kang Seojeong|script-title=ko:\uc704\ub300\ud55c \uc720\ud639\uc790\u2019 \ucd9c\uc5f0\ud655\uc815 \u2018\ub300\uc138\ub4e4\uc758 \ub9cc\ub0a8|url=http://osen.mt.co.kr/article/G1110803382|work=OSEN|date=December 28, 2017|accessdate=January 2, 2018|language=ko}}</ref><ref name=gt>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201712281721028194159_2|title=Red Velvet's Joy, Woo Do-hwan to star in new drama 'Great Temptation'|date=December 28, 2017|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201803081722173556134_2|title=Joy to be 'The Great Seducer' of love|date=March 8, 2018|website=Kpop Herald}}</ref> Joy released an OST for the drama titled \"OMG!\", and went on to be nominated for Best Actress at the MBC Drama Awards, Rookie of The Year at the MBC Drama Awards,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=609&aid=0000038901|title=MBC Drama Awards 2018 \uc18c\uc9c0\uc12d '\ub370\ubdd4 23\ub144 \ub9cc\uc5d0 \uccab \ub300\uc0c1'(mbc\uc5f0\uae30\ub300\uc0c1)[\ud3ec\ud1a0\uc5d4HD]|website=entertain.naver.com|language=ko|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref> Popularity Award (Drama Actress Category) at The Seoul Awards,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.stardailynews.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=216732|title=The 2nd Seoul Awards Red Velvet Joy|date=October 5, 2018|website=Star Daily News|accessdate=December 12, 2018}}</ref> and Actress of the Year at the Brand of the Year Awards.<ref name=\":4\" />\n[[File:Joy Park at Bulgari Event 2019.jpg|thumb|225x225px|Joy at [[Bulgari]] event in 2019]]\nJust in time for Red Velvet's summer mini album ''[[Summer Magic (EP)|Summer Magic]]'', Joy graced [[Nylon (magazine)|Nylon]] Korea's August 2018 issue cover.<ref>Lee Da Huin. [http://www.fashionn.com/board/read_new.php?table=1024&number=25226 \uc870\uc774, \uc2f1\uadf8\ub7ec\uc6b4 \ub9e4\ub825 \uac00\ub4dd\ud55c \uc2a4\ud2b8\ub9ac\ud2b8 \uce90\uc8fc\uc5bc\ub8e9 '\ud587\uc0b4\ubcf4\ub2e4 \ub208\ubd80\uc154'] ''Fashion N'', July 17, 2018. Retrieved August 22, 2018.</ref> Joy was also named as the new model and official endorser for ''Fitz Super Clear Beer''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dt.co.kr/contents.html?article_no=2018070402109932817014|title=BTOB's Yook Sungjae And Red Velvet's Joy Named As Models For Fitz \ub86f\ub370\uc8fc\ub958, `\ud53c\uce20 \uc218\ud37c\ud074\ub9ac\uc5b4` \ubaa8\ub378\uc5d0 \uc870\uc774\u00b7\uc721\uc131\uc7ac \ubc1c\ud0c1|last=|first=|date=|website=www.dt.co.kr|language=ko|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> Shortly after, Joy was chosen as one of the hosts of [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]]'s new variety show ''[[Pajama Friends]],'' alongside [[Song Ji-hyo]], [[Jang Yoon-ju]], and [[Cheng Xiao]].<ref>Ha Su Jeong.[http://osen.mt.co.kr/article/G1110969593 B'\ud30c\uc790\ub9c8 \ud504\ub80c\uc988' \uc1a1\uc9c0\ud6a8x\uc7a5\uc724\uc8fcx\uc870\uc774x\uc131\uc18c, 4MC \ud655\uc815..8\uc6d4 \uccab\ucd2c\uc601] ''OSEN'', July 17, 2018. Retrieved August 22, 2018.</ref> In October 2018, Joy released the song \"Dream Me\" (with [[NCT (band)|NCT]]'s [[Mark Lee (singer)|Mark]]) for the soundtrack of the [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]] drama ''[[The Ghost Detective]].'' \"Dream Me\" went on to be listed in Spotify's Top Korean OSTs of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/playlist/37i9dQZF1DX6HNmsqZ1nyc|title=Top Korean OSTs of 2019, a playlist by Spotify|website=Spotify|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, it was announced that Joy was chosen to be the main host of Asia's most popular beauty program [[OnStyle]]'s ''Get It Beauty'' alongside [[Jang Yoon-ju]], with Joy praised for her effort in developing and showcasing her variety skills in numerous programs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=312&aid=0000368585|title=\ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3 \uc870\uc774, '\uac9f\uc787\ubdf0\ud2f0 2019' \uba54\uc778 MC \ud569\ub958\u2026\ubdf0\ud2f0 \ud504\ub85c\uadf8\ub7a8 \uccab \ub3c4\uc804|website=entertain.naver.com|language=ko|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref> In May 2019, Joy was officially announced as the new muse of [[Amorepacific Corporation|Amore Pacific]]'s professional makeup brand, ''eSpoir''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=117&aid=0003221734|script-title=ko:'\ub354\uc704\ub0a0\ub9ac\ub294 \uc0c1\ud07c\ud568'\u2026\uc870\uc774, \uacfc\uc999\ubbf8 \ud130\uc9c0\ub294 \ube44\uc8fc\uc5bc|website=entertain.naver.com|language=ko|access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref> Later that month, Joy was nominated for Beauty Icon of the Year at the Brand of the Year Awards.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://abk.kcforum.co.kr/|title=\uc62c\ud574\uc758 \ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc \ub300\uc0c1|website=abk.kcforum.co.kr|access-date=2019-05-30}}</ref> In October 2019, Joy was also nominated for Beauty Icon at the Korea First Brand Awards.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://fba.kcforum.co.kr/|title=\ub300\ud55c\ubbfc\uad6d \ud37c\uc2a4\ud2b8\ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc \ub300\uc0c1|website=fba.kcforum.co.kr|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref> \n\nIn December 2019, Joy was announced as a cast member of the new variety show, ''[[Handsome Tigers]]'', alongside [[Cha Eun-woo]], [[Lee Sang-yoon]], [[Yoo Seon-ho]], and [[Seo Jang-hoon]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://mosen.mt.co.kr/article/G1111270703|title=\uc11c\uc7a5\ud6c8, \ub18d\uad6c\uc608\ub2a5 \uc9c1\uc811 \ub860\uce6d..\uc774\uc0c1\uc724\u00b7\ucc28\uc740\uc6b0\u00b7\uae40\uc2b9\ud604\u00b7\uc720\uc120\ud638 \ub4f1 \ud655\uc815 [\uacf5\uc2dd]|last=OSEN|date=2019-12-02|website=mosen.mt.co.kr|language=ko|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref><ref name=\":ht\">{{Cite web|url= https://n.news.naver.com/entertain/article/117/0003321296 |title= [MD\ud3ec\ud1a0] \ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3 \uc870\uc774 '\ud589\ubcf5\ud55c \ud578\uc12c\ud0c0\uc774\uac70\uc988 \ub9e4\ub2c8\uc800' |last=Naver|date=January 9, 2020|website=Naver|language=ko|access-date=January 19, 2020}}</ref> In the K-pop Radar Year-End Chart, Joy was named as \"2019 Hot Instagrammer - Female\" and confirmed to have the most [[Instagram]] followers among K-pop artists who opened an account in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://n.news.naver.com/entertain/article/112/0003243731|title=\ubc29\ud0c4\uc18c\ub144\ub2e8, 2019\ub144 \ucf00\uc774\ud31d \ub808\uc774\ub354 \uc120\uc815 \ubba4\ube44 \uc870\ud68c\uc218 \ucd5c\ub300 \ubc43\uc9c0 \ud68d\ub4dd\u2025\uc6d4\ub4dc\ud074\ub798\uc2a4 \uc131\uc801|website=n.news.naver.com|language=ko|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Joy was selected as the new official model and face of ''Aveda'', with the brand stating that Joy was chosen because of her bright and healthy image across various fields including music and acting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://m.anewsa.com/article_sub3.php?number=2042778|title=\uc544\ubca0\ub2e4, 2020\ub144 \uc0c8\ub85c\uc6b4 \uacf5\uc2dd \ubaa8\ub378 \ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3 \uc870\uc774 \ubc1c\ud0c1!|date=2020-01-02|website=m.anewsa.com|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> In February 2020, Joy was invited as a VIP guest of [[Michael Kors]] to attend [[New York Fashion Week]], with [[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] calling Joy \"one of K-pop\u2019s brightest stars\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/slideshow/red-velvet-joy-michael-kors-fall-2020-diary|title=Red Velvet Singer Joy\u2019s Fashion Week Debut Was Extra Sweet|last=|first=|date=|website=Vogue|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> In the same month, Joy was nominated as Best Female Variety Idol by the 2020 Brand Customer Loyalty Awards.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nIn March 2020, Joy released the song \"Introduce Me a Good Person\" for the soundtrack of the [[TVN (South Korean TV channel)|tvN]] drama ''[[Hospital Playlist]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kndaily.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=148141|title=\ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3 \uc870\uc774, tvN \ub4dc\ub77c\ub9c8 \u2018\uc2ac\uae30\ub85c\uc6b4 \uc758\uc0ac\uc0dd\ud65c\u2019 OST \uc8fc\uc778\uacf5 - \uacbd\ub0a8\ub370\uc77c\ub9ac|website=www.kndaily.co.kr|language=ko|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> Joy went on to be ranked #2 on the [[Melon (online music service)|Melon]] Female Solo Artist Chart<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.melon.com/artistplus/artistchart/index.htm?chartGubunCode=FS0000|title=Melon|website=www.melon.com|language=ko|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>, with the song reaching #1 on Bugs and Naver, #1 on the Melon OST Hot Track Chart, and charting at #8 on the Instiz iChart.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instiz.net/spage/8|title=\"iChart\"|website=instiz.net|language=ko|accessdate=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n==Personal life==\nIn February 2015, Joy graduated from [[School of Performing Arts Seoul]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Lee Ji Sook|url=http://mwave.interest.me/en/kpop-news/article/87186/photo-a-pinks-ha-young-red-velvets-joy-baps-zelo-and-more-graduate-from-high-school|title=A Pink\u2032s Ha Young, Red Velvet\u2032s Joy, B.A.P\u2032s Zelo and More Graduate from High School|publisher=MWave|date=February 11, 2015|accessdate=March 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018214729/http://mwave.interest.me/en/kpop-news/article/87186/photo-a-pinks-ha-young-red-velvets-joy-baps-zelo-and-more-graduate-from-high-school|archive-date=October 18, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In February 2020, Joy donated 10 million won for the [[Community Chest of Korea]] to help support those affected by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=202002281117102410|title=\ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3 \uc2ac\uae30-\uc870\uc774-\uc608\ub9ac, \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \ud655\uc0b0\ubc29\uc9c0 \uc704\ud574 3\ucc9c\ub9cc\uc6d0 \uae30\ubd80(\uacf5\uc2dd)|date=2020-02-28|website=\ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3 \uc2ac\uae30-\uc870\uc774-\uc608\ub9ac, \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \ud655\uc0b0\ubc29\uc9c0 \uc704\ud574 3\ucc9c\ub9cc\uc6d0 \uae30\ubd80(\uacf5\uc2dd) - \uc190\uc5d0 \uc7a1\ud788\ub294 \ub274\uc2a4 \ub208\uc5d0 \ubcf4\uc774\ub294 \ub274\uc2a4 - \ub274\uc2a4\uc5d4|language=ko|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{see also|Red Velvet discography}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Sales\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Gaon Chart|KOR]]<br><ref name=\"Gaon Singles\">{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/|title=Gaon Chart|publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association}}\n* {{cite web|title=Young Love|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=ALL&targetTime=17&hitYear=2016&termGbn=week|date=April 30, 2016|accessdate=October 28, 2016}}\n* {{cite web|title=Always In My Heart|url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?serviceGbn=ALL&termGbn=week&hitYear=2016&targetTime=46&nationGbn=T|date=November 18, 2016|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}\n* {{cite web|title=Yeowooya|url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?serviceGbn=ALL&termGbn=week&hitYear=2017&targetTime=12&nationGbn=T|date=March 25, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2017}}\n* {{cite web|title=I'm Okay|url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?serviceGbn=ALL&termGbn=week&hitYear=2017&targetTime=13&nationGbn=T|date=April 1, 2017|accessdate=April 6, 2017}}\n* {{cite web|title=Introduce Me a Good Person|url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=ALL&targetTime=14&hitYear=2020&termGbn=week|date=Apri